      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Downloads\\\\logo_deconstruction.html\", \"offset\": 881}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\logo_deconstruction.html</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n881:                 logo is cheaper to screen-print (less ink coverage) and works on any garment colour — the black areas become\n882:                 transparent when overlaying on dark fabric, leaving only the warm gradient visible.\n883:                 </p>\n884:             </div>\n885: \n886:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n887:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">bold sans-serif typeface</div>\n888:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n889:                 <strong>Why \"bold\" not \"regular\", \"medium\", or \"heavy\":</strong> The detected weight corresponds to a \"Bold\" or\n890:                 \"ExtraBold\" font weight (700–800 in CSS terms). \"Regular\" (400) would be too light to stand beside the massive\n891:                 continent silhouette. \"Medium\" (500) would read as a caption, not a brand name. \"Heavy\" (900) is used for\n892:                 headlines, not logos — it compresses letterforms and reduces legibility at small sizes. Bold strikes the right\n893:                 balance: visible at 16px (avatar size) without losing letterform distinctiveness.\n894:                 </p>\n895:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n896:                 <strong>Why \"sans-serif\" not \"serif\", \"script\", \"display\", or \"hand-drawn\":</strong> Sans-serif typefaces (without\n897:                 decorative feet/strokes) convey modernity, clarity, and directness. Serif faces feel traditional and literary\n898:                 — wrong for a dance brand that positions itself as contemporary. Script faces are personal and elegant but\n899:                 terrible for acronym legibility (connected cursive makes letters hard to distinguish). Display faces are\n900:                 decorative and lose readability at small sizes. Hand-drawn communicates artisan/craft — not the right tone for\n901:                 an organisation that also runs a structured classroom programme.\n902:                 </p>\n903:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n904:                 <strong>Scenarios:</strong> (1) On mobile screens, the bold sans-serif \"AFJ\" remains readable even when the logo\n905:                 is displayed at 40px wide (navigation bar). (2) In multilingual contexts (Welsh/English bilingual signage at\n906:                 AFJ events), a sans-serif typeface avoids the cultural baggage of serif fonts (which can be read as \"English-only\"\n907:                 or \"colonial\" in Wales). (3) When the logo is embroidered on uniforms, bold sans-serif strokes ensure thread\n908:                 density is sufficient — thin serifs would become tangled or lose definition in embroidery.\n909:                 </p>\n910:             </div>\n911: \n912:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n913:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">bounding box (content BBox)</div>\n914:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n915:                 <strong>Why \"bounding box\" not \"boundary rectangle\", \"frame\", or \"container\":</strong> In computer graphics and\n916:                 design tools, \"bounding box\" is the standard term for the smallest axis-aligned rectangle that entirely encloses\n917:                 a set of non-background pixels. \"Boundary rectangle\" is unnecessarily longer. \"Frame\" implies a visible border\n918:                 or decorative edge. \"Container\" is a UI layout concept (e.g., <code>&lt;div&gt;</code>), not a geometric measure.\n919:                 \"BBox\" is the accepted abbreviation in SVG, GIS, and 3D graphics.\n920:                 </p>\n921:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n922:                 <strong>Why it exists:</strong> The bounding box tells you exactly where the \"action\" happens in the logo: what\n923:                 portion of the 974×992 canvas actually contains visible content (the continent). It reveals the margins, the\n924:                 centring offset, and the proportional size of the graphic.\n925:                 </p>\n926:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n927:                 <strong>What it helps with:</strong> (1) Layout decisions — if you need to place the logo in a 400×400 box, the\n928:                 BBox tells you to scale so that the 468×462 content area fits, not the full 974×992 canvas. (2) Spacing\n929:                 calculations — the 44px horizontal offset (center at 443 vs canvas center 487) tells designers that the logo\n930:                 appears slightly left-weighted, which matters when pairing it with text or centring it on a page. (3) When\n931:                 cropping the logo for specific uses (app icon, favicon), the BBox tells you the minimal crop rectangle without\n932:                 cutting into the continent shape. (4) For automated layout systems (responsive CSS, PDF generation), the BBox\n933:                 provides machine-readable geometry tokens.\n934:                 </p>\n935:             </div>\n936: \n937:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n938:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">brand identity</div>\n939:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n940:                 <strong>Why \"brand identity\" not \"logo\", \"visual identity\", or \"brand guidelines\":</strong> \"Brand identity\" is the\n941:                 holistic system of visual, verbal, and experiential elements that represent an organisation. The logo is a\n942:                 <em>component</em> of brand identity, not the identity itself. \"Visual identity\" is a subset (colours, typography,\n943:                 imagery). \"Brand guidelines\" are the <em>documentation</em> of the identity. We use \"brand identity\" here because\n944:                 the dual colour system (warm logo palette + cool classroom palette) is a strategic choice about how the brand\n945:                 feels across different contexts — not just what the logo looks like.\n946:                 </p>\n947:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n948:                 <strong>What it enables / scenarios:</strong> (1) A strong brand identity means AFJ Cardiff can be recognised\n949:                 without the logo — just the warm gradient colours or the bold sans-serif AFG acronym on a poster is enough.\n950:                 (2) The dual system (identity = warm, UI = cool) creates a \"contextual brand\" that feels appropriate in each\n951:                 environment: energetic for marketing, calm for education. (3) For franchising or scaling, a documented brand\n952:                 identity ensures every chapter/classroom uses consistent colours, even when local instructors design their own\n953:                 materials.\n954:                 </p>\n955:             </div>\n956: \n957:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n958:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">brick red (#c06060)</div>\n959:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n960:                 <strong>Why \"brick red\" not \"terracotta\", \"rust\", \"burnt sienna\", or \"coral\":</strong> #c06060 = RGB(192,96,96) —\n961:                 a mid-tone red with equal parts red and green (both 96), making it a muted, slightly greyish red. \"Terracotta\"\n962:                 (#e2725b) is more orange-leaning — this colour is equally balanced between warm and cool red, giving it a\n963:                 solid, grounded feel. \"Rust\" implies an orange-brown (#b7410e). \"Burnt sienna\" is more orange (#e97451).\n964:                 \"Coral\" (#ff7f50) is too bright and pinkish. \"Brick red\" is the most evocative: it suggests the colour of\n965:                 clay bricks — natural, earthy, structural, solid. It implies permanence and foundation, which is why it appears\n966:                 at 11.7% of the accent: it's the anchor in the warm palette, providing stability between the brighter gold\n967:                 and the more intense crimson.\n968:                 </p>\n969:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n970:                 <strong>Why it exists:</strong> Without brick red, the warm palette would skew either too yellow (gold + amber)\n971:                 or too purple (crimson). Brick red bridges the gap — it's warm but not hot, red but not aggressive. It gives\n972:                 the gradient a \"coals in a fire\" quality, where some areas glow bright (amber) and others glow deep and steady\n973:                 (brick).\n974:                 </p>\n975:             </div>\n976:         </div>\n977: \n978:         <div id=\"gloss-C\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n979:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">C</h3>\n980: \n981:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n982:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">canvas (HTML5 Canvas element)</div>\n983:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n984:                 <strong>Why \"canvas\" not \"image element\", \"SVG container\", or \"drawing surface\":</strong> This page uses the\n985:                 HTML5 <code>&lt;canvas&gt;</code> API — a bitmap drawing surface that allows pixel-level manipulation via\n986:                 JavaScript. Unlike an <code>&lt;img&gt;</code> tag (which only displays static images), the canvas enables\n987:                 dynamic overlay rendering: grid lines, bounding boxes, edge points, and center markers drawn in real-time as\n988:                 the user clicks buttons. \"SVG container\" uses vector paths (scalable, event-driven). \"Drawing surface\" is too\n989:                 generic. \"Canvas\" is the precise W3C API name and tells developers exactly which rendering strategy is used.\n990:                 </p>\n991:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n992:                 <strong>Why a canvas-based viewer instead of a static image with CSS overlays:</strong> CSS overlays (pseudo-elements,\n993:                 box-shadows) can't dynamically redraw, can't show/hide individual layers without toggling CSS classes on many\n994:                 elements, and can't draw arbitrary shapes (like the continent centroid dot or the edge-point scatter). Canvas\n995:                 gives a single, programmatic surface where all 6 overlay modes are rendered in ~20 lines of JS — no DOM to\n996:                 manage, no z-index stacking, no style recalculations.\n997:                 </p>\n998:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n999:                 <strong>What it enables / scenarios:</strong> (1) Designers can inspect the logo at pixel level — overlay modes\n1000:                 reveal structural decisions (centering, margins, symmetry) that would be invisible in a static image.\n1001:                 (2) Students learning design theory can toggle overlays to understand how composition, balance, and colour\n1002:                 distribution work in a real brand mark. (3) The canvas viewer is reusable for any logo — swap the Base64\n1003:                 image data and update the token constants, and the overlay engine works for a different brand.\n1004:                 </p>\n1005:             </div>\n1006: \n1007:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1008:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">canvas (logo file canvas — 974 × 992)</div>\n1009:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1010:                 <strong>Why \"canvas\" for the logo dimensions not \"image size\" or \"artboard\":</strong> \"Canvas\" is the standard\n1011:                 term in design software (Photoshop, Illustrator, Figma) for the working area that contains the artwork. \"Image\n1012:                 size\" includes the pixel dimensions of the rendered output. \"Artboard\" is an Adobe-specific term for a\n1013:                 multi-canvas document. Using \"canvas\" aligns with designer vocabulary and makes the token immediately\n1014:                 understandable to anyone who has used a design tool.\n1015:                 </p>\n1016:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1017:                 <strong>Why 974 × 992 — unconventional dimensions:</strong> These dimensions are not a standard size (like\n1018:                 1024×1024 or 800×800). The designer likely arrived at them by fitting the continent silhouette at a specific\n1019:                 scale and then padding it with margins until the proportions felt balanced. The near-square ratio (487:496)\n1020:                 suggests the designer wanted a square logo (for profile photos, social media, app icons) but the continent\n1021:                 shape naturally demanded slightly more height than width.\n1022:                 </p>\n1023:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1024:                 <strong>Scenarios where this matters:</strong> (1) If a developer tries to resize the logo to 500×500 using\n1025:                 <code>width: 500px; height: 500px</code> without preserving aspect ratio, the continent will appear 0.5%\n1026:                 squished vertically — barely noticeable but technically incorrect. The token <code>aspect.ratio: 0.9819</code>\n1027:                 tells them to use <code>height: calc(width / 0.9819)</code>. (2) For favicon generation (usually square), the\n1028:                 near-square means minimal cropping is needed. (3) For print layout, the physical size at 216 DPI (~4.5\" × 4.6\")\n1029:                 tells printers whether it fits in standard frames, business-card spaces, or brochure panels.\n1030:                 </p>\n1031:             </div>\n1032: \n1033:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1034:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">centroid (continent centroid)</div>\n1035:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1036:                 <strong>Why \"centroid\" not \"centre\" or \"midpoint\":</strong> \"Centre\" of a shape is ambiguous — it could mean the\n1037:                 visual centre, the geometric centre, or the centre of the bounding box. \"Midpoint\" is usually reserved for the\n1038:                 middle of a line segment. \"Centroid\" is the precise mathematical term for the arithmetic mean of all pixel\n1039:                 positions within a shape (the \"centre of mass\"). For the irregular African continent silhouette, the centroid\n1040:                 is not at the same position as the bounding-box centre — it shifts toward the densest part of the shape. Using\n1041:                 \"centroid\" signals that this is a calculated value, not an estimate.\n1042:                 </p>\n1043:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1044:                 <strong>Why it's at (443, 451):</strong> The continent shape has higher pixel density in its lower portion (the\n1045:                 bulge of West Africa and the southern tip), pulling the centroid down and slightly left. Compare to the canvas\n1046:                 centre (487, 496) — the 44px leftward offset and 45px upward offset indicate the continent is positioned\n1047:                 slightly left and high, creating an asymmetrical balance that feels dynamic rather than static.\n1048:                 </p>\n1049:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1050:                 <strong>What it helps with:</strong> (1) When placing the logo in a layout, the centroid is the point you would\n1051:                 align with other elements' centroids — not the bounding-box edge — for the most visually balanced composition.\n1052:                 (2) For animation purposes (if the logo were to rotate or pulse), the centroid is the correct pivot point.\n1053:                 (3) The centroid offset (44px) is a design token you can use to programme alignment in CSS: compensate by\n1054:                 shifting the logo 44px right to centre precisely.\n1055:                 </p>\n1056:             </div>\n1057: \n1058:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1059:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">classroom / UI environment</div>\n1060:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1061:                 <strong>Why \"classroom\" not \"website\" or \"learning platform\":</strong> \"Classroom\" refers to the specific Canva-based\n1062:                 educational portal AFJ Cardiff uses for its structured courses. It is a distinct digital environment from the\n1063:                 main marketing website. \"UI environment\" acknowledges that the classroom interface has its own colour system\n1064:                 (navy blues, charcoal) that is separate from the brand's logo palette. Calling it \"classroom\" grounds the\n1065:                 distinction in real-world usage — it's the place where students see course materials, not the place where\n1066:                 visitors learn about the organisation.\n1067:                 </p>\n1068:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1069:                 <strong>Why a separate colour system for classroom:</strong> Educational interfaces benefit from calm, focused\n1070:                 colour schemes — bright warm colours (gold, crimson) are exciting but tiring over extended reading/learning\n1071:                 sessions. Navy blues (#202040, #204060) are psychologically associated with concentration, trust, and\n1072:                 professionalism. The dual system lets AFJ Cardiff be \"energetic and exciting\" in its marketing while being\n1073:                 \"calm and trustworthy\" in its classroom — the best of both brand personalities.\n1074:                 </p>\n1075:             </div>\n1076: \n1077:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1078:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">cohesive lockup</div>\n1079:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1080:                 <strong>Why \"cohesive lockup\" not \"logo combo\", \"grouped logo\", or \"brand block\":</strong> \"Lockup\" is the\n1081:                 industry-standard term in brand design (used by Pentagram, Wolff Olins, and every major branding agency) for\n1082:                 the fixed spatial relationship between a symbol and a wordmark — they are \"locked\" together and must not be\n1083:                 separated. \"Cohesive\" adds that the typography and continent use the same gradient, creating visual unity.\n1084:                 </p>\n1085:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1086:                 <strong>Why lockup exists:</strong> The fixed position (AFJ above continent, CARDIFF below) means the brand is\n1087:                 always recognisable regardless of context. If someone separated \"AFJ\" from the continent silhouette, it would\n1088:                 look like a different brand. The lockup prevents logo misuse by non-designers creating materials.\n1089:                 </p>\n1090:             </div>\n1091: \n1092:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1093:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">colour economy</div>\n1094:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1095:                 <strong>Why \"colour economy\" not \"limited palette\" or \"minimal colours\":</strong> \"Colour economy\" is the\n1096:                 deliberate principle of using a small number of colours to maximise impact — it's an active design choice, not\n1097:                 a limitation. \"Limited palette\" sounds like a constraint (budget, technical). \"Minimal colours\" describes the\n1098:                 result but not the strategy. \"Colour economy\" frames 92.1% black as a <em>strength</em>: the logo invests its\n1099:                 colour budget in the 7.6% of warm gradient, making every coloured pixel count.\n1100:                 </p>\n1101:             </div>\n1102: \n1103:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1104:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">colour (design) token</div>\n1105:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1106:                 <strong>Why \"design token\" not \"colour variable\" or \"style guide value\":</strong> \"Design token\" is the formal\n1107:                 term from the Design Tokens W3C Community Group for a named, platform-agnostic value (colour, spacing, type\n1108:                 scale) that can be shared across design tools and code. \"Colour variable\" is implementation-specific (CSS\n1109:                 custom property, Sass variable, SwiftUI Color). \"Style guide value\" is too vague — all styles have values.\n1110:                 \"Design token\" signals that these values are the <em>single source of truth</em> that feeds both the Figma\n1111:                 design system and the production CSS.\n1112:                 </p>\n1113:             </div>\n1114: \n1115:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1116:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">complementary color theory</div>\n1117:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1118:                 <strong>Why invoked here:</strong> The warm logo palette (hue ~30°: orange-amber) and the cool classroom palette\n1119:                 (hue ~220°: blue-navy) sit 190° apart on the colour wheel — very close to exact complementary (180°). This\n1120:                 means when the warm logo is placed on a navy classroom background, the colours \"complete\" each other, creating\n1121:                 maximum perceived contrast without visual vibration (which happens with near-neighbour hues like red-on-orange).\n1122:                 Complementary colour pairings are proven to increase recall by up to 23% in marketing studies (Hall &amp; Hanna,\n1123:                 2004).\n1124:                 </p>\n1125:             </div>\n1126: \n1127:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1128:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">connected components (29 regions)</div>\n1129:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1130:                 <strong>Why \"connected components\" not \"shapes\", \"blobs\", or \"segments\":</strong> \"Connected components\" is the\n1131:                 exact computer-vision term from image segmentation. A connected component is a set of pixels that are\n1132:                 adjacent (4- or 8-connected) and share the same non-background value. \"Shapes\" implies intentional geometry\n1133:                 (circles, rectangles). \"Blobs\" is colloquial (OpenCV's SimpleBlobDetector). \"Segments\" is ambiguous (could mean\n1134:                 contiguous regions or line segments). Using the correct computer-vision terminology enables the reader to\n1135:                 replicate the analysis with standard tools: <code>cv2.connectedComponentsWithStats()</code> or\n1136:                 <code>skimage.measure.label()</code>.\n1137:                 </p>\n1138:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1139:                 <strong>Why 29 components:</strong> The continent silhouette is 1 component (the largest). Each letter in \"AFJ\"\n1140:                 and \"CARDIFF\" creates multiple components (e.g., \"A\" has a counter/hole that counts as internal whitespace,\n1141:                 \"F\" is one component, \"J\" is one, each letter in \"CARDIFF\" is 1 component each + counters = ~11 components\n1142:                 for the wordmark). Anti-aliasing pixels at edges can create tiny isolated \"island\" components of 1–3 pixels,\n1143:                 adding to the count.\n1144:                 </p>\n1145:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1146:                 <strong>Scenarios:</strong> (1) If converting to SVG, each connected component maps to a distinct <code>&lt;path&gt;</code>\n1147:                 element. The component count tells you how many paths to expect. (2) For accessibility, screen readers can\n1148:                 navigate between semantic regions — the component count helps estimate how many traversable elements a\n1149:                 visually-impaired user would encounter. (3) Styling each component individually (e.g., a staggered entrance\n1150:                 animation) is possible because the component boundaries are known.\n1151:                 </p>\n1152:             </div>\n1153: \n1154:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1155:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">construction walkthrough</div>\n1156:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1157:                 <strong>Why \"construction walkthrough\" not \"steps\" or \"how it's made\":</strong> \"Construction\" implies\n1158:                 layer-by-layer assembly (like an architect's construction drawing). \"Walkthrough\" implies guided navigation\n1159:                 with numbered steps — not just a list but a path from first principle to finished mark. Together they signal\n1160:                 that the reader should follow in order, not skip to step 6. \"Steps\" is too vague (CSS steps? staircase steps?).\n1161:                 \"How it's made\" is informal and doesn't convey the analytical depth of the section.\n1162:                 </p>\n1163:             </div>\n1164: \n1165:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1166:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">copper / bronze (#c08060)</div>\n1167:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1168:                 <strong>Why \"copper/bronze\" not \"rust\", \"brown\", \"terracotta\", or \"burnt orange\":</strong> #c08060 =\n1169:                 RGB(192,128,96). The red and green channels are dominant and nearly equal (192R vs 128G), with less blue (96B),\n1170:                 producing a warm reddish-brown with orange undertones. This is the exact hue of polished copper (a specific\n1171:                 metal, not a generic \"brown\"). \"Rust\" (#a0522d) is darker and more orange-brown. \"Brown\" is too generic\n1172:                 (encompasses everything from #654321 to #d2b48c). \"Terracotta\" (#e2725b) is lighter and more pink-orange.\n1173:                 \"Burnt orange\" (#cc5500) is more orange and less brown. \"Copper\" is the most accurate material reference and\n1174:                 carries connotations of: Africa's copper belt (Zambia/DRC), traditional African metalwork, and the warm glow\n1175:                 of copper cookware and jewellery. \"Bronze\" is added because the colour sits at the boundary — it's slightly\n1176:                 darker than bright copper, leaning toward bronze's deeper reddish-brown.\n1177:                 </p>\n1178:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1179:                 <strong>Why 19.0% — the most dominant accent colour:</strong> Copper anchors the warm palette. It is the\n1180:                 colour that appears most in the continent silhouette because it forms the \"base\" of the gradient (the start\n1181:                 stop at 20%). Every pixel in the gradient area that falls near the starting edge or in the mid-tones will be\n1182:                 copper-ish. It dominates because the gradient is weighted toward the copper end.\n1183:                 </p>\n1184:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1185:                 <strong>Scenarios / what it enables:</strong> (1) Copper reads as \"earthy\" and \"natural\" — appropriate for an\n1186:                 organisation rooted in African cultural heritage. (2) It has high contrast against black (the base) and navy\n1187:                 (the classroom UI), making it visible in both colour systems. (3) In print, copper gradients can be replaced\n1188:                 with metallic ink (Pantone 876 C) for premium materials (business cards, certificates). (4) For digital\n1189:                 accessibility, copper on black has a contrast ratio of ~7.2:1, exceeding WCAG AAA for normal text.\n1190:                 </p>\n1191:             </div>\n1192: \n1193:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1194:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">counterbalanced</div>\n1195:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1196:                 <strong>Why \"counterbalanced\" not \"balanced\" or \"offset\":</strong> \"Counterbalanced\" implies an intentional\n1197:                 opposite weight — the large continent at top is visually \"heavy\"; the small wordmark at bottom is intentionally\n1198:                 small so it doesn't compete — it counterbalances rather than matches. \"Balanced\" would suggest equal weight\n1199:                 above and below. \"Offset\" is purely geometric (x/y displacement). \"Counterbalanced\" communicates the design\n1200:                 principle: unequal weights arranged to create equilibrium, like a seesaw with a heavy child sitting closer to\n1201:                 the fulcrum.\n1202:                 </p>\n1203:             </div>\n1204: \n1205:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1206:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">crimson / rose (#c04060)</div>\n1207:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1208:                 <strong>Why \"crimson/rose\" not \"pink\", \"magenta\", \"burgundy\", or \"raspberry\":</strong> #c04060 = RGB(192,64,96)\n1209:                 — a mid-to-dark red with a distinct blue undertone (green=64, blue=96). \"Pink\" is too light and low-saturation\n1210:                 (#ffc0cb). \"Magenta\" is pure purple-red (#ff00ff). \"Burgundy\" (#800020) is much darker and purer red.\n1211:                 \"Raspberry\" (#e30b5d) is brighter. \"Crimson\" is the precise hue: deep red with a blue/cool undertone — the\n1212:                 colour of the traditional crimson dye (from the kermes insect, historically significant in African and\n1213:                 Mediterranean trade). \"Rose\" is appended because the colour has a \"rose-red\" quality — it's not a pure red,\n1214:                 it's slightly bluish like a dark rose petal. This duality (crimson = power, passion, blood; rose = love,\n1215:                 beauty, delicacy) makes the colour versatile: it can be read as fierce (crimson) or beautiful (rose) depending\n1216:                 on context.\n1217:                 </p>\n1218:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1219:                 <strong>Why 12.3% — second most dominant accent:</strong> Crimson is the \"hot end\" of the warm gradient. It\n1220:                 appears at the 100% stop and bleeds into surrounding pixels. In a gradient from copper to crimson, the\n1221:                 crimson pixels are the smallest population (only the far end) but visually the most impactful — they're the\n1222:                 \"flame tips\" of the fire metaphor.\n1223:                 </p>\n1224:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1225:                 <strong>Scenarios:</strong> (1) Crimson as the hover-state colour on buttons creates urgency without the alarm\n1226:                 of pure red. (2) In the scrollytelling page, crimson drives the \"energy/passion\" narrative for Azonto dance.\n1227:                 (3) For accessibility, crimson on black (ratio ~5.9:1) passes WCAG AA for large text, and at 19px+ body text.\n1228:                 (4) In the Classroom UI, crimson is used sparingly (alerts, badges, active states) where navy would be too\n1229:                 passive.\n1230:                 </p>\n1231:             </div>\n1232:         </div>\n1233: \n1234:         <div id=\"gloss-D\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1235:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">D</h3>\n1236: \n1237:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1238:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">design token extraction</div>\n1239:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1240:                 <strong>Why \"extraction\" not \"analysis\" or \"measurement\":</strong> \"Extraction\" implies pulling machine-readable\n1241:                 values (tokens) out of a raw bitmap — a one-way conversion from visual to structured data. \"Analysis\" is\n1242:                 broader (could include qualitative assessment). \"Measurement\" suggests physical dimension only. \"Extraction\"\n1243:                 is the term used in design-to-code tools (Zeplin, Figma API, Anima) for generating tokens from design files.\n1244:                 </p>\n1245:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1246:                 <strong>What it enables:</strong> (1) Brand consistency — tokens ensure every developer and designer uses the\n1247:                 exact same values. (2) Automated workflows — tokens can feed CSS variables, Android XML colours, iOS asset\n1248:                 catalogues, and design tool libraries simultaneously. (3) Version control — token changes are tracked in git\n1249:                 and reviewable. (4) Responsive scaling — proportional tokens (margin.left = 21.5%) adapt to any container\n1250:                 size.\n1251:                 </p>\n1252:             </div>\n1253: \n1254:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1255:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">DPI (dots per inch)</div>\n1256:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1257:                 <strong>Why \"216 DPI\" not 72, 150, or 300:</strong> 72 DPI is the legacy screen standard (original Macintosh),\n1258:                 far too low for print. 150 DPI is acceptable for newsprint. 300 DPI is the standard for high-quality print.\n1259:                 216 DPI sits between — it's the resolution Adobe Illustrator exports at when you set the \"Export for Screens\"\n1260:                 resolution to 2× (2 × 108 = 216). The designer likely created the logo as a vector 108 DPI artboard and\n1261:                 exported at 2× for Retina screens. This is actually a screen-optimised resolution, not a print resolution.\n1262:                 216 DPI will produce acceptable print at up to ~5\" wide — for larger prints (posters, banners), a vector\n1263:                 source should be used.\n1264:                 </p>\n1265:             </div>\n1266: \n1267:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1268:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">dual color system</div>\n1269:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1270:                 <strong>Why \"dual color system\" not \"multiple palettes\" or \"contextual colours\":</strong> \"Dual\" specifies exactly\n1271:                 two colour sets with defined roles. \"Multiple palettes\" suggests 3+ sets, which is not the case here. \"Contextual\n1272:                 colours\" is implementation-focused (CSS media queries) rather than strategic. \"Dual color system\" is a design\n1273:                 strategy term used by major brands (Google has dual Material Design colour systems for light/dark themes; Slack\n1274:                 has brand colours and product colours). It signals intentionality.\n1275:                 </p>\n1276:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1277:                 <strong>Why AFJ Cardiff needs this:</strong> Dance organisations often struggle with a split personality —\n1278:                 they want to feel exciting for performances but professional for classes. The dual system resolves this without\n1279:                 losing brand recognition: the warm palette is the \"voice\" (emotional, energetic), the cool palette is the\n1280:                 \"space\" (functional, educational). Both contain the same brand DNA (the logo appears in both) but serve\n1281:                 different moods.\n1282:                 </p>\n1283:             </div>\n1284:         </div>\n1285: \n1286:         <div id=\"gloss-E\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1287:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">E</h3>\n1288: \n1289:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1290:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">edge density (0.91%)</div>\n1291:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1292:                 <strong>Why \"edge density\" not \"line count\" or \"stroke percentage\":</strong> \"Edge density\" is the computer-vision\n1293:                 metric: the ratio of edge pixels (where adjacent pixels have different values, detected by Canny/Sobel operators)\n1294:                 to total pixels. 0.91% means less than 1% of the image is an \"edge\". \"Line count\" is meaningless (a single thick\n1295:                 line = 1 line, same as a thin line). \"Stroke percentage\" only applies to vector paths, not bitmaps. Edge density\n1296:                 directly measures visual complexity — higher density = busier, more detailed.\n1297:                 </p>\n1298:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1299:                 <strong>Why 0.91% — extremely low:</strong> Compare: a detailed photograph has edge density of 15–40%, a\n1300:                 line-art illustration ~3–8%, a minimalist logo ~0.5–1.5%. AFJ Cardiff's logo at 0.91% is in the \"ultra-minimalist\"\n1301:                 range, comparable to Nike (~0.8%), Apple (pre-rainbow: ~0.6%), and Mastercard (overlapping circles: ~0.7%).\n1302:                 This is intentional: minimal edge density means the logo is simple enough to be instantly recognised, reproduced\n1303:                 at any size, and remembered after a single glance.\n1304:                 </p>\n1305:             </div>\n1306: \n1307:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1308:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">edge detection (overlay mode)</div>\n1309:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1310:                 <strong>Why this overlay exists:</strong> The edge detection overlay visualises the exact boundaries where the\n1311:                 warm gradient meets the black background. In the deconstruction page, it simulates a Canny edge detector by\n1312:                 marking edge points (centroid, character boundaries) with red dots. This is educational — users can toggle\n1313:                 between \"Original\" (no edges visible due to anti-aliasing) and \"Edge Detect\" to see where the shape boundary\n1314:                 algorithmically lies.\n1315:                 </p>\n1316:             </div>\n1317:         </div>\n1318: \n1319:         <div id=\"gloss-F\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1320:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">F</h3>\n1321: \n1322:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1323:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">file.size (65,024 B)</div>\n1324:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1325:                 <strong>Why report file size in a design token:</strong> File size affects page load time, which affects SEO\n1326:                 (Google Core Web Vitals), user retention (53% of mobile users abandon pages taking >3 seconds to load), and\n1327:                 bandwidth costs. A 65KB logo is well-optimised — the baseline PNG at 974×992 would be ~3MB uncompressed. The\n1328:                 PNG compression reduces it 47×. This token tells developers: \"Your image optimisation is working; don't\n1329:                 re-compress.\" The token also serves as a quality gate: if a future version of the logo exceeds 200KB, the\n1330:                 token change triggers a review (is the optimisation still adequate?).\n1331:                 </p>\n1332:             </div>\n1333: \n1334:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1335:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">fire-and-earth glow</div>\n1336:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1337:                 <strong>Why \"fire-and-earth\" not \"warm glow\" or \"sunset effect\":</strong> \"Fire-and-earth\" is a compound metaphor\n1338:                 that marries two elements: fire (crimson, energy, passion, movement — the dance) and earth (copper, stability,\n1339:                 heritage, grounding — the African continent). \"Warm glow\" is technically accurate but emotionally flat.\n1340:                 \"Sunset effect\" implies the colour of a specific time of day, which is too literal and not brand-ownable.\n1341:                 \"Fire-and-earth\" is memorable, evocative, and uniquely ownable by AFJ Cardiff — no competitor can claim the\n1342:                 same phrase. It also maps to the three Azonto dance steps (The Signal = fire, The Grounding = earth, The\n1343:                 Dialogue = the interaction between both).\n1344:                 </p>\n1345:             </div>\n1346:         </div>\n1347: \n1348:         <div id=\"gloss-G\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1349:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">G</h3>\n1350: \n1351:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1352:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">gold / brass (#c08040)</div>\n1353:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1354:                 <strong>Why \"gold/brass\" not \"yellow\", \"ochre\", \"saffron\", or \"marigold\":</strong> #c08040 = RGB(192,128,64) —\n1355:                 significantly more red than green (192R vs 128G), giving it a warm, slightly brownish gold. \"Yellow\" is pure\n1356:                 (255,255,0) — this is not that. \"Ochre\" (#cc7722) is more orange-brown. \"Saffron\" (#f4c430) is brighter and\n1357:                 more yellow. \"Marigold\" (#eaa221) is more orange. \"Gold\" is the aspirational colour — it carries connotations\n1358:                 of excellence, value, and \"gold medal\". \"Brass\" is appended because the hex is not pure metallic gold\n1359:                 (#ffd700 or #d4af37) — it's a more subdued, aged gold that resembles brass. This prevents false expectations\n1360:                 of a shiny, reflective metallic gold when the logo is printed — it's a matte, earthy gold.\n1361:                 </p>\n1362:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1363:                 <strong>Why 12.6% — almost as dominant as copper:</strong> Gold appears as the mid-stop in the gradient\n1364:                 (50%). It's the transition colour between copper and amber, representing the \"brightest warm\" point before\n1365:                 the gradient shifts toward crimson's cool warmth.\n1366:                 </p>\n1367:             </div>\n1368: \n1369:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1370:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">gradient dithering</div>\n1371:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1372:                 <strong>Why mentioned alongside anti-aliasing as a colour multiplier:</strong> Dithering — the intentional\n1373:                 introduction of noise patterns to approximate a gradient in a limited colour space — is what happens when a\n1374:                 continuous gradient is saved as an 8-bit PNG. Instead of smooth transitions, the PNG's palette constraint\n1375:                 creates tiny pixel-level variations that appear as \"grain\". This grain is composed of new colours not in the\n1376:                 original gradient, inflating the unique colour count. Without dithering, the gradient would use only the\n1377:                 6 colour stops — with dithering, you get 7,955 intermediate colours. This is a feature, not a bug: dithered\n1378:                 gradients look smoother to the human eye than banded (non-dithered) gradients.\n1379:                 </p>\n1380:             </div>\n1381: \n1382:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1383:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">grid overlay</div>\n1384:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1385:                 <strong>Why a grid overlay:</strong> The grid divides the 974×992 canvas into 20×20 proportional cells\n1386:                 (each 48.7×49.6px), providing a reference for margin proportions. It answers: \"How far is 21.5% from the\n1387:                 left edge?\" — about 4 grid columns. The grid colour is copper-toned (#c08060 at 30% opacity) to match the\n1388:                 brand palette rather than using a neutral grey. This lets the grid blend subtly into the logo gradient\n1389:                 without distracting from it.\n1390:                 </p>\n1391:             </div>\n1392:         </div>\n1393: \n1394:         <div id=\"gloss-H\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1395:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">H</h3>\n1396: \n1397:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1398:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">hierarchy (visual hierarchy)</div>\n1399:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1400:                 <strong>Why \"hierarchy\" not \"importance order\" or \"reading sequence\":</strong> \"Visual hierarchy\" is the design\n1401:                 principle that arranges elements so the eye sees them in a specific order: AFJ (most prominent) → continent\n1402:                 (second) → CARDIFF (third). \"Importance order\" is the same concept but less precise in layout terms.\n1403:                 \"Reading sequence\" implies linear text flow (left-to-right, top-to-bottom), but logo perception is\n1404:                 simultaneous — hierarchy describes what jumps out first, not what is read first.\n1405:                 </p>\n1406:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1407:                 <strong>Why documented as a token:</strong> If a junior designer moves \"CARDIFF\" to the top and makes it bold,\n1408:                 the hierarchy breaks — viewers would read the location before the brand name. Documenting \"brand name dominates,\n1409:                 location is secondary\" as a design rule prevents this. In code, hierarchy is enforced by CSS: <code>font-size:\n1410:                 clamp(2.5rem, 5vw, 4rem)</code> for AFJ vs <code>font-size: 1rem</code> for CARDIFF.\n1411:                 </p>\n1412:             </div>\n1413: \n1414:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1415:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">horizontal projection analysis (14 text rows)</div>\n1416:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1417:                 <strong>Why \"horizontal projection analysis\" not \"row counting\" or \"text detection\":</strong> Horizontal projection\n1418:                 analysis is a specific image-processing technique: sum all non-background pixel values per row, then find peaks\n1419:                 in the resulting 1D signal. Each peak corresponds to a text row. This is different from \"row counting\" (which\n1420:                 requires knowing the font size) and \"text detection\" (which uses OCR or ML). \"Horizontal projection analysis\"\n1421:                 is transparent about the method, allowing reproducibility in any image-processing library\n1422:                 (<code>np.sum(binary_image, axis=1)</code>).\n1423:                 </p>\n1424:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n\n(Output capped at 50 KB. Showing lines 881-1424. Use offset=1425 to continue.)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
      "timestamp": 1781576293507
    },
    {
      "type": "thought",
      "text": "Let me continue reading the rest of the file to see all glossary entries and the ADR section.",
      "timestamp": 1781576296440
    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"offset\": 1425, \"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Downloads\\\\logo_deconstruction.html\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\logo_deconstruction.html</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1425:                 <strong>Why ~14 rows instead of exactly 14:</strong> The tilde (~) indicates the count is approximate because:\n1426:                 (1) gradient anti-aliasing creates weak projections that may or may not be counted depending on the threshold;\n1427:                 (2) some rows may be ascender/descender extensions (the \"F\" in AFJ extends above the other letters);\n1428:                 (3) very small edge-only rows may be artifacts. The ~14 means \"approximately 14 text rows, give or take 1–2.\"\n1429:                 </p>\n1430:             </div>\n1431: \n1432:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1433:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">hue separation (~190°)</div>\n1434:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1435:                 <strong>Why \"hue separation\" not \"colour difference\" or \"contrast\":</strong> \"Hue separation\" specifically\n1436:                 measures the angular distance between two colours on the colour wheel — not their saturation or brightness\n1437:                 difference. \"Colour difference\" is ambiguous (could mean Delta-E, HSL distance, or perceptual difference).\n1438:                 \"Contrast\" is usually brightness-based (WCAG contrast ratio). Hue separation is the technical metric used in\n1439:                 colour scheme generation (monochromatic = 0°, analogous = 30–60°, complementary = 180°).\n1440:                 </p>\n1441:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1442:                 <strong>Why ~190°, not exactly 180° (true complementary):</strong> The warm palette's dominant hue is ~30°\n1443:                 (orange-amber) and the classroom navy is ~220° (blue). 220 − 30 = 190°. True complementary would be 30 + 180\n1444:                 = 210° (a greener blue). The 10° offset means the pairing is a \"split complementary\" — slightly less tense\n1445:                 than a pure complementary, which can feel like vibration. This makes the pairing more comfortable for extended\n1446:                 reading (classroom context).\n1447:                 </p>\n1448:             </div>\n1449:         </div>\n1450: \n1451:         <div id=\"gloss-K\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1452:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">K</h3>\n1453: \n1454:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1455:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">kerning (tightly kerned)</div>\n1456:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1457:                 <strong>Why \"tightly kerned\" not \"close letters\" or \"condensed\":</strong> \"Kerning\" is the adjustment of space\n1458:                 between individual letter pairs. \"Tightly kerned\" means the AF, FJ pairs have reduced negative space compared\n1459:                 to the font's default. This is different from \"condensed\" (which squishes the entire font width). Tight kerning\n1460:                 makes the acronym feel like a single firm block rather than three separate letters — essential for a logo mark\n1461:                 that needs to be read as a unit. \"Kerning\" is the correct typographic term, understood by designers and\n1462:                 type foundries. \"Close letters\" is imprecise. \"Condensed\" is wrong (it refers to font width, not letter\n1463:                 spacing).\n1464:                 </p>\n1465:             </div>\n1466:         </div>\n1467: \n1468:         <div id=\"gloss-L\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1469:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">L</h3>\n1470: \n1471:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1472:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">leading</div>\n1473:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1474:                 <strong>Why \"leading\" not \"line height\" or \"line spacing\":</strong> \"Leading\" (pronounced \"ledding\") is the\n1475:                 traditional typesetting term for vertical space between baselines — named after the lead strips used in\n1476:                 letterpress. In CSS, <code>line-height</code> is the equivalent. \"Line spacing\" is a word-processor term.\n1477:                 Using \"leading\" signals typographic sophistication and aligns with design-tool terminology (InDesign, Figma,\n1478:                 Illustrator). \"Minimal leading\" means the text rows are close together, creating a dense, solid typographic\n1479:                 block that mirrors the solidity of the continent silhouette.\n1480:                 </p>\n1481:             </div>\n1482: \n1483:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1484:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">linear gradient (135°)</div>\n1485:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1486:                 <strong>Why \"linear gradient\" not \"colour blend\" or \"ramp\":</strong> \"Linear gradient\" is the CSS/design-tool\n1487:                 term for a colour transition along a straight line at a specified angle. \"Colour blend\" is ambiguous (could\n1488:                 mean any blend mode). \"Ramp\" is a 3D rendering term for texture filtering.\n1489:                 </p>\n1490:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1491:                 <strong>Why 135° (south-east diagonal):</strong> 0° = top-to-bottom, 90° = left-to-right, 135° = top-left to\n1492:                 bottom-right diagonal. This angle:\n1493:                 (1) Creates a natural light-like effect — as if the continent is illuminated from the upper-left (the\n1494:                 Western sunrise direction relative to Africa).\n1495:                 (2) Avoids the static feel of horizontal (90°) or vertical (0°) gradients.\n1496:                 (3) Puts the brightest colour (amber/gold) at the upper-left corner (where the eye naturally starts scanning)\n1497:                 and the darkest accent (crimson) at lower-right, guiding the eye across the continent.\n1498:                 (4) Works for both portrait and landscape usage — a 135° diagonal looks intentional in any orientation.\n1499:                 </p>\n1500:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1501:                 <strong>Scenarios for changing the angle:</strong> If the logo is used on a left-aligned layout (e.g., business\n1502:                 card), the gradient might shift to 45° (top-right illuminate) to point toward the text. If used on a dark\n1503:                 gradient background, the angle might flip to maintain contrast. These adjustments are safe as long as the\n1504:                 colour stops remain the same.\n1505:                 </p>\n1506:             </div>\n1507: \n1508:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1509:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">lockup (typographic lockup)</div>\n1510:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1511:                 <strong>Why \"lockup\" not \"layout\" or \"arrangement\":</strong> A lockup is a fixed, non-negotiable spatial\n1512:                 relationship between brand elements. In AFJ Cardiff's logo, the acronym, continent, and wordmark positions\n1513:                 are locked — you cannot move \"AFJ\" below the continent or put \"CARDIFF\" beside it. This is a legal and design\n1514:                 constraint: any variation could be considered a different logo. \"Layout\" implies flexibility. \"Arrangement\"\n1515:                 suggests temporary placement.\n1516:                 </p>\n1517:             </div>\n1518:         </div>\n1519: \n1520:         <div id=\"gloss-M\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1521:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">M</h3>\n1522: \n1523:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1524:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">margins (asymmetric margin distribution)</div>\n1525:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1526:                 <strong>Why not \"padding\" or \"white space\":</strong> \"Margins\" is the correct term for the space between the\n1527:                 content and the canvas edge in a static composition. \"Padding\" is CSS-specific (inside a box). \"White space\"\n1528:                 is any empty area, including internal gaps between elements.\n1529:                 </p>\n1530:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1531:                 <strong>Why asymmetric (21.5% left, 30.5% right, 24% top, 29.4% bottom):</strong>\n1532:                 <br>• Left (21.5%) is smallest — the eye enters from the left; a narrow left margin brings the content closer\n1533:                 to the viewer.\n1534:                 <br>• Right (30.5%) is largest — the extra space on the right creates an \"open\" feeling, as if the content is\n1535:                 breathing into the right side. Also compensates for the continent's 44px left-weighted centroid.\n1536:                 <br>• Top (24%) — moderate, allows space for the \"AFJ\" acronym to breathe above the continent.\n1537:                 <br>• Bottom (29.4%) — largest vertical margin, anchors the composition and prevents the wordmark from feeling\n1538:                 crammed.\n1539:                 </p>\n1540:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1541:                 <strong>Scenarios:</strong> (1) If the logo is used in a square profile picture (Facebook, Instagram), a\n1542:                 centred crop would cut more from the right and bottom — designers should pad the right side rather than centre.\n1543:                 (2) For a horizontal logo variant (banner, website header), the 21.5% left margin means the content can be\n1544:                 left-aligned without feeling pushed to the edge. (3) The asymmetric margins are a <em>brand signal</em> —\n1545:                 they show the logo is intentionally dynamic, not mechanically centred.\n1546:                 </p>\n1547:             </div>\n1548: \n1549:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1550:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">minimalist linework</div>\n1551:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1552:                 <strong>Why \"minimalist linework\" not \"simple design\" or \"clean\":</strong> \"Simple\" implies lacking complexity\n1553:                 (maybe unfinished). \"Clean\" is subjective and overused. \"Minimalist linework\" describes a specific aesthetic:\n1554:                 the design uses the minimum possible number of edge pixels (0.91% edge density) to communicate the continent\n1555:                 shape, embracing the \"less is more\" philosophy of minimalist design (Bauhaus, Swiss Style, Dieter Rams).\n1556:                 </p>\n1557:             </div>\n1558: \n1559:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1560:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">\"major.regions: 1\"</div>\n1561:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1562:                 <strong>Why \"major.regions\" not \"large shapes\":</strong> A \"major region\" is defined as a connected component\n1563:                 with area > 1,000 px² in this analysis. There is exactly 1 such region: the African continent silhouette.\n1564:                 The acronym letters (\"AFJ\") are each ~300–700 px², making them minor regions. \"CARDIFF\" letters are even\n1565:                 smaller (~86–240 px²). This token quantifies the \"one dominant shape, multiple supporting details\" structure.\n1566:                 </p>\n1567:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1568:                 <strong>Why care:</strong> If a logo has 0 major regions, it's all text (no graphic mark). If it has 3+ major\n1569:                 regions, the logo is complex and may not reproduce well at small sizes. Having 1 major region is ideal — the\n1570:                 continent is the single recognisable shape, everything else is detail.\n1571:                 </p>\n1572:             </div>\n1573:         </div>\n1574: \n1575:         <div id=\"gloss-N\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1576:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">N</h3>\n1577: \n1578:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1579:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">navy (classroom palette: #202040, #204060, #204080)</div>\n1580:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1581:                 <strong>Why \"navy\" not \"dark blue\", \"indigo\", or \"midnight blue\":</strong> #202040 = a very dark blue with\n1582:                 only 32 red and 32 green, 64 blue. #204060 = slightly lighter, more blue (B=96). #204080 = even more blue\n1583:                 (B=128). These are classic navy blues — official uniform colour of navies worldwide, associated with trust,\n1584:                 authority, and professionalism. \"Dark blue\" is too generic (any dark hue of blue). \"Indigo\" (#4b0082) is\n1585:                 more purple. \"Midnight blue\" (#191970) is closer but not standardised. \"Navy\" is the most recognised, most\n1586:                 standardised term — Pantone 19-4013 TCX (Dark Navy) and Pantone 19-4023 TCX (Navy Peony) cover this range.\n1587:                 </p>\n1588:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1589:                 <strong>Why the three-tier navy system:</strong> Three navies at different darkness levels create depth without\n1590:                 needing additional colours. #202040 serves as the primary background (darkest, least distracting). #204060 is\n1591:                 used for cards/surfaces (slightly lighter, creates visual separation from background). #204080 is used for\n1592:                 interactive elements (buttons, links) — the increasing blue signals interactivity without resorting to a\n1593:                 bright blue that would clash with the warm logo.\n1594:                 </p>\n1595:             </div>\n1596: \n1597:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1598:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">near-square</div>\n1599:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1600:                 <strong>Why \"near-square\" not \"almost square\" or \"rectangle\":</strong> \"Near-square\" communicates that the\n1601:                 intent was to create a square logo, but the content's natural proportions (continent + text stack) pushed it\n1602:                 to 487:496 — 0.5% from a perfect 1:1 square. This is deliberate and should be preserved. Calling it a\n1603:                 \"rectangle\" would lose the design intent — you might think a 1:1 crop is acceptable, but cropping the height\n1604:                 would cut into the wordmark.\n1605:                 </p>\n1606:             </div>\n1607: \n1608:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1609:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">negative space</div>\n1610:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1611:                 <strong>Why \"negative space\" not \"empty space\" or \"blank area\":</strong> \"Negative space\" is the design term\n1612:                 for the area around and between subject matter — it's not \"empty\", it's an active compositional element.\n1613:                 The 29.4% bottom margin is negative space that prevents the logo from feeling bottom-heavy. \"Empty space\"\n1614:                 implies nothingness. \"Blank area\" is not a design term. \"Negative space\" signals that the space was\n1615:                 intentionally sized to perform a function (balancing the composition).\n1616:                 </p>\n1617:             </div>\n1618: \n1619:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1620:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">near-perfect (horizontal symmetry at 94.5%)</div>\n1621:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1622:                 <strong>Why \"near-perfect\" not \"almost perfect\" or \"high\":</strong> 94.5% is extraordinarily high for a\n1623:                 handcrafted logo — a perfectly symmetric image (like a circle) would score 100%. The 5.5% asymmetry comes from\n1624:                 the natural irregularity of the African coastline (no continent is perfectly symmetric) and anti-aliasing\n1625:                 differences on each side. \"Near-perfect\" communicates that the designer deliberately made the outline as close\n1626:                 to balanced as possible while respecting the subject matter's natural asymmetry.\n1627:                 </p>\n1628:             </div>\n1629:         </div>\n1630: \n1631:         <div id=\"gloss-O\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1632:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">O</h3>\n1633: \n1634:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1635:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">optimised PNG</div>\n1636:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1637:                 <strong>Why \"optimised PNG\" not \"compressed\" or \"saved as PNG\":</strong> \"Compressed\" could mean lossy\n1638:                 compression (JPEG) which would destroy the gradient. \"Saved as PNG\" doesn't indicate whether optimisation was\n1639:                 applied. \"Optimised\" means the file was run through a PNG optimiser (pngcrush, optipng, pngquant) that:\n1640:                 (1) removes metadata (EXIF, colour profiles not needed here),\n1641:                 (2) applies best-filter strategy per scanline,\n1642:                 (3) selects optimal Huffman encoding. The result (65KB from ~3MB raw = 47:1 compression) confirms effective\n1643:                 optimisation.\n1644:                 </p>\n1645:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1646:                 <strong>What it helps with:</strong> (1) Page load speed — a 65KB image downloads in ~0.3s on 4G vs ~2s for\n1647:                 unoptimised. (2) SEO — Google's PageSpeed Insights penalises uncompressed images. (3) Version control —\n1648:                 optimised PNGs change less between versions (consistent compression), making git diffs more readable.\n1649:                 </p>\n1650:             </div>\n1651: \n1652:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1653:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">overlay (overlay modes)</div>\n1654:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1655:                 <strong>Why \"overlay\" not \"filter\", \"layer\", or \"view\":</strong> \"Overlay\" is the correct computer-graphics term\n1656:                 for rendering additional visual information on top of an existing image without altering the original. \"Filter\"\n1657:                 implies image processing (blur, sharpen). \"Layer\" is a Photoshop term that suggests editability. \"View\" is too\n1658:                 broad. Six overlay modes (Original, Grid, Bounding Box, Edge Detect, Centers, All) each render independent\n1659:                 diagnostic information on top of the original logo — the \"All\" mode combines all 5 diagnostic overlays\n1660:                 simultaneously.\n1661:                 </p>\n1662:             </div>\n1663:         </div>\n1664: \n1665:         <div id=\"gloss-P\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1666:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">P</h3>\n1667: \n1668:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1669:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">pale gold (#c0a060)</div>\n1670:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1671:                 <strong>Why \"pale gold\" not \"beige\", \"cream\", or \"wheat\":</strong> #c0a060 = RGB(192,160,96) — a desaturated\n1672:                 golden tan. \"Beige\" (#f5f5dc) is much lighter. \"Cream\" (#fffdd0) is even lighter and more yellow. \"Wheat\"\n1673:                 (#f5deb3) is lighter. \"Pale gold\" is accurate: it's gold that has been \"diluted\" with white/grey, appearing\n1674:                 at only 1.5% of accent pixels — just enough to provide highlight reflections at the brightest points of the\n1675:                 gradient, giving the continent a subtle \"sheen\" at the top-left corner.\n1676:                 </p>\n1677:             </div>\n1678: \n1679:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1680:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">print-ready (~4.5\" × 4.6\" physical)</div>\n1681:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1682:                 <strong>Why \"print-ready\" not \"high resolution\":</strong> A 974×992 pixel image at 216 DPI produces a physical\n1683:                 print of ~4.51\" × 4.59\" (974÷216, 992÷216). This is the size of a large badge, small sticker, or business\n1684:                 card graphic. \"Print-ready\" communicates that the image has sufficient resolution for print at this size, but\n1685:                 it's <em>not</em> suitable for large-format print (A4 posters, banners) — that would need a vector source\n1686:                 (SVG/AI/EPS). \"High resolution\" is relative — 216 DPI is acceptable for office printing but below the 300 DPI\n1687:                 standard for commercial print. The token tells the printer the exact physical dimensions and resolution,\n1688:                 preventing the \"this image is too small for print\" error.\n1689:                 </p>\n1690:             </div>\n1691: \n1692:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1693:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">primary color / primary element</div>\n1694:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1695:                 <strong>Why \"primary\" not \"main\" or \"base\":</strong> \"Primary\" in design systems means \"first in importance,\n1696:                 used most frequently\". \"Primary color\" is the brand's dominant colour (here, black #000000 at 92.1%). \"Main\"\n1697:                 is informal. \"Base\" is a specific role in palette hierarchies. \"Primary element\" is the continent silhouette,\n1698:                 not the colour. \"Primary\" is the standard term in Material Design, Lightning, Polaris, and Spectrum design\n1699:                 systems — using it aligns AFJ Cardiff's tokens with industry conventions.\n1700:                 </p>\n1701:             </div>\n1702:         </div>\n1703: \n1704:         <div id=\"gloss-R\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1705:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">R</h3>\n1706: \n1707:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1708:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">RGB (no alpha)</div>\n1709:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1710:                 <strong>Why \"RGB (no alpha)\" not \"true colour\" or \"24-bit\":</strong> \"RGB\" means three 8-bit channels (Red,\n1711:                 Green, Blue). \"No alpha\" means no transparency channel — the background is explicitly black (#000) rather\n1712:                 than transparent. This is a deliberate choice: most logos use transparency (alpha channel or PNG transparency)\n1713:                 so they can overlay on any background. AFJ Cardiff's logo does NOT have transparency — the designer decided\n1714:                 the logo should always be presented on black (or a very dark background). This is a constraint: you cannot\n1715:                 place this logo on a white website header without creating a harsh black rectangle around it.\n1716:                 </p>\n1717:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1718:                 <strong>Why no alpha was chosen:</strong> (1) The gradient's \"fire-and-earth glow\" effect requires a black\n1719:                 background to achieve sufficient contrast — on a white background, the warm gradient would look dull and\n1720:                 washed out. (2) The logo was designed for the specific use case of dark-themed websites and merchandise,\n1721:                 where a solid black background is acceptable. (3) If transparency were needed, the logo would need a\n1722:                 separate \"light mode\" variant with inverted colours (white/gold on transparent).\n1723:                 </p>\n1724:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1725:                 <strong>Scenarios where this matters:</strong> (1) If a developer places this logo in an HTML <code>&lt;img&gt;</code>\n1726:                 tag on a white background, they should add <code>filter: drop-shadow(0 0 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.5))</code> or\n1727:                 <code>background: #000</code> to maintain the intended look. (2) For social media profile pictures (which use\n1728:                 circular crops), the black background outside the circle is visible — the crop must be applied to the full\n1729:                 square, not trimmed. (3) For merchandise printing, the black background means the print shop uses less ink\n1730:                 (black is cheapest) and the logo appears as a floating gradient on dark garments.\n1731:                 </p>\n1732:             </div>\n1733:         </div>\n1734: \n1735:         <div id=\"gloss-S\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1736:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">S</h3>\n1737: \n1738:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1739:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">scrollytelling</div>\n1740:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1741:                 <strong>Why \"scrollytelling\" not \"scroll-driven animation\", \"parallax story\", or \"scroll narrative\":</strong>\n1742:                 \"Scrollytelling\" is the industry term (coined by the New York Times graphics desk, popularised by r/DataIsBeautiful\n1743:                 and the Scrollama library) for a specific technique: scrolling drives the narrative — as you scroll, content\n1744:                 changes, images animate, and the story progresses in sync with progress. \"Scroll-driven animation\" describes\n1745:                 the mechanism but not the narrative purpose. \"Parallax story\" is one type (background moves slower than\n1746:                 foreground). \"Scroll narrative\" is descriptive but clunky. \"Scrollytelling\" is self-documenting: scroll +\n1747:                 storytelling.\n1748:                 </p>\n1749:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1750:                 <strong>Why AFJ Cardiff uses it:</strong> Azonto dance cannot be explained in text alone — it must be felt.\n1751:                 Scrollytelling lets the user control the pace: they pause, see a dance pose, read its meaning, scroll further,\n1752:                 see the next pose. This \"active reading\" increases retention by 40–60% over passive video watching (Scrollytelling\n1753:                 vs. Video studies, 2018–2023).\n1754:                 </p>\n1755:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1756:                 <strong>What it enables:</strong> (1) The 3 Azonto poses (Signal → Grounding → Dialogue) map to scroll progress\n1757:                 0% → 33% → 66% → 100%, creating a frame-scrubbing effect. (2) Users can re-scroll to review poses, which\n1758:                 they cannot do with auto-playing video. (3) The parallax drift (text and silhouettes move at different speeds)\n1759:                 creates a cinematic depth effect without video files, keeping the page lightweight.\n1760:                 </p>\n1761:             </div>\n1762: \n1763:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1764:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">silhouette extraction (3 dancer silhouettes)</div>\n1765:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1766:                 <strong>Why \"silhouette extraction\" not \"cut out\" or \"background removal\":</strong> \"Extraction\" in image\n1767:                 processing means separating foreground from background algorithmically. The 3 dancers were extracted from\n1768:                 azonto.jfif via chroma key (green/red screen removal) + contour detection (finding the largest connected\n1769:                 regions that represent human shapes). \"Cut out\" is manual (Photoshop). \"Background removal\" is one step of\n1770:                 many — extraction also includes contour cropping, ensuring each dancer is tightly bounded by their own\n1771:                 silhouette box rather than split arbitrarily.\n1772:                 </p>\n1773:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1774:                 <strong>Why contour detection over 3-way split:</strong> A 3-way split would assume the image divides into\n1775:                 equal horizontal thirds — wrong, because dancers are different widths (486, 578, 534 px). Contour detection\n1776:                 finds each dancer's exact bounding region, resulting in tighter crops with less wasted space and more accurate\n1777:                 frame transitions.\n1778:                 </p>\n1779:             </div>\n1780: \n1781:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1782:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">symmetry (horizontal 94.5% / vertical 93.4%)</div>\n1783:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1784:                 <strong>Why \"symmetry\" not \"balance\" or \"alignment\":</strong> \"Symmetry\" is mathematically measurable: flip the\n1785:                 image horizontally, compare pixel-by-pixel to original, and count matching pixels ÷ total pixels = 94.5%.\n1786:                 \"Balance\" is perceptual, not quantifiable. \"Alignment\" refers to edge/center relationships.\n1787:                 </p>\n1788:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1789:                 <strong>Why 94.5% vs 93.4%:</strong> Horizontal symmetry (left-right mirror) is higher because the designer\n1790:                 centred the continent carefully — any large left/right imbalance would look unprofessional. Vertical symmetry\n1791:                 (top-bottom mirror) is lower because the logo is intentionally top-heavy (large continent above, small wordmark\n1792:                 below). A vertically symmetric logo would put \"AFJ\" at bottom as well, which would look bizarre. The gap\n1793:                 between H and V symmetry (1.1%) quantifies the design's intentional asymmetry.\n1794:                 </p>\n1795:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1796:                 <strong>Scenarios:</strong> (1) If the logo is flipped horizontally for a mirror layout (e.g., on a vehicle's\n1797:                 passenger side), the 94.5% symmetry means it will still look correct — the 5.5% asymmetry is imperceptible\n1798:                 to most viewers. (2) For animation (a subtle breathing/pulsing effect), the centroid offset (44px) should\n1799:                 be the centre of the pulse, not the canvas centre.\n1800:                 </p>\n1801:             </div>\n1802:         </div>\n1803: \n1804:         <div id=\"gloss-T\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1805:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">T</h3>\n1806: \n1807:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1808:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">text region (22px height per row)</div>\n1809:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1810:                 <strong>Why \"text region\" not \"line\" or \"text block\":</strong> \"Text region\" is the bounding rectangle of a\n1811:                 detected horizontal band of text in the projection analysis. \"Line\" implies a single row of text (which this\n1812:                 is, for each row). \"Text block\" includes multiple lines with padding. The 22px height per row tells\n1813:                 typographers the approximate font size — a 22px region height with standard leading suggests a font size of\n1814:                 ~16–18px (depending on ascender/descender ratio).\n1815:                 </p>\n1816:             </div>\n1817: \n1818:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1819:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">top-heavy nature</div>\n1820:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1821:                 <strong>Why \"top-heavy\" not \"top-weighted\" or \"upper-focused\":</strong> \"Top-heavy\" is a direct visual analogy to\n1822:                 physical objects that are heavier at the top — they feel dynamic and slightly precarious, which creates visual\n1823:                 interest. \"Top-weighted\" is neutral (just means more weight above). \"Upper-focused\" describes eye direction,\n1824:                 not weight distribution. \"Top-heavy\" implies the designer consciously put the larger element (continent) above\n1825:                 the smaller one (wordmark), making the logo feel active rather than stable — appropriate for a dance\n1826:                 organisation.\n1827:                 </p>\n1828:             </div>\n1829: \n1830:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1831:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">typography (typography.lines ~14)</div>\n1832:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1833:                 <strong>Why \"typography.lines\" not \"text.rows\" or \"font.lines\":</strong> \"Typography\" refers to the art and\n1834:                 technique of arranging type — the token specifically measures the number of horizontal rows occupied by \"AFJ\"\n1835:                 and \"CARDIFF\" combined. \"Font.lines\" would imply lines of the same font (confusing). \"Text.rows\" is ambiguous\n1836:                 (can include non-text rows). \"Typography.lines\" is the most precise token path: it tells you this is about\n1837:                 typesetting, not general content rows. The ~14 lines include ascenders, descenders, and internal spacing.\n1838:                 </p>\n1839:             </div>\n1840:         </div>\n1841: \n1842:         <div id=\"gloss-U\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1843:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">U</h3>\n1844: \n1845:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1846:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">unique colours (7,961)</div>\n1847:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text_dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1848:                 <strong>Why \"unique colours\" not \"colour count\" or \"palette size\":</strong> \"Unique colours\" explicitly means\n1849:                 distinct RGB triplets in the pixel data — not the number of colours in the palette (which for a 24-bit PNG\n1850:                 can be up to 16.7 million). 7,961 unique colours from a logo with only 5 named accent colours seems\n1851:                 contradictory: the explanation is that anti-aliasing (edge smoothing between black and gradient) and gradient\n1852:                 dithering (noise pattern to simulate smooth transitions) together create ~7,955 intermediate colours. This is\n1853:                 normal and expected — it means the gradient is high-quality and the anti-aliasing is working correctly.\n1854:                 </p>\n1855:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1856:                 <strong>What it enables:</strong> (1) If the unique colour count were &lt;100, the logo would look \"posterised\"\n1857:                 (banded, low-quality gradient). 7,961 tells quality assurance that the gradient render is smooth.\n1858:                 (2) If the count exceeds 50,000 (for this size), it may indicate JPEG compression artifacts (should have\n1859:                 stayed PNG). (3) For SVG conversion, fewer unique colours means simpler vector paths — 7,961 is a reasonable\n1860:                 count that won't bloat the SVG file.\n1861:                 </p>\n1862:             </div>\n1863: \n1864:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1865:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">upward-left weighting</div>\n1866:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1867:                 <strong>Why \"upward-left weighting\" not \"top-left gravity\" or \"corner focus\":</strong> \"Weighting\" is the design\n1868:                 term for distributing visual mass to direct eye movement. \"Upward-left\" describes the specific vector: the\n1869:                 eye lands on the acronym (top), follows the continent down, reads the wordmark at bottom. But because the\n1870:                 continent is 44px left of centre and the left margin (21.5%) is narrower than the right (30.5%), the entire\n1871:                 composition feels pulled upward and leftward — a dynamic orientation that prevents static symmetry. \"Top-left\n1872:                 gravity\" sounds like a physics force, not a design choice. \"Corner focus\" suggests the corner itself is\n1873:                 important (it's not — it's the composition's orientation that matters).\n1874:                 </p>\n1875:             </div>\n1876:         </div>\n1877: \n1878:         <div id=\"gloss-V\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1879:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">V</h3>\n1880: \n1881:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1882:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">visual hierarchy</div>\n1883:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1884:                 <strong>Why \"visual hierarchy\" not \"reading order\":</strong> Reading order implies sequential consumption\n1885:                 (word 1 → word 2 → word 3). Visual hierarchy is about what the eye is drawn to first, second, and third in\n1886:                 a single glance — it's simultaneous, not sequential. In this logo: the acronym \"AFJ\" (largest, top) is seen\n1887:                 first, the continent silhouette (colourful, central) is seen second, and the wordmark \"CARDIFF\" (smaller,\n1888:                 bottom) is read third. This hierarchy communicates: \"who we are (AFJ) → where we're from (Africa) → where we\n1889:                 operate (Cardiff)\".\n1890:                 </p>\n1891:             </div>\n1892: \n1893:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1894:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">visual unity</div>\n1895:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1896:                 <strong>Why \"visual unity\" not \"consistency\" or \"matching\":</strong> \"Visual unity\" means all elements feel\n1897:                 like they belong to the same entity — the same gradient is applied to both the continent and the typography,\n1898:                 creating a visual \"echo\" that binds text and image. \"Consistency\" is mechanical (same font, same size).\n1899:                 \"Matching\" implies exact replica (same colour applied identically), which undersells the intentional\n1900:                 repetition of the gradient as a unifying device.\n1901:                 </p>\n1902:             </div>\n1903:         </div>\n1904: \n1905:         <div id=\"gloss-W\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n1906:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">W</h3>\n1907: \n1908:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1909:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">warm earth-and-fire accent palette</div>\n1910:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1911:                 <strong>Why \"warm earth-and-fire\" not \"autumn colours\" or \"sunset palette\":</strong> \"Autumn colours\" is seasonal\n1912:                 and temporary (appropriate for a fall campaign, not a permanent brand). \"Sunset\" is also temporal and\n1913:                 geographically specific (different sunsets look different). \"Warm earth-and-fire\" is permanent, elemental,\n1914:                 and evocative: \"earth\" = copper, bronze, brown (African continent, grounding, heritage); \"fire\" = crimson,\n1915:                 amber, gold (energy, dance, passion). This palette is unique, ownable, and directly tied to the organisation's\n1916:                 mission (Afro dance as a connection between earth/heritage and fire/passion).\n1917:                 </p>\n1918:             </div>\n1919: \n1920:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1921:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">white silhouette (scrollytelling)</div>\n1922:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1923:                 <strong>Why \"white silhouette\" not \"cutout\" or \"image\":</strong> The dancer silhouettes in the scrollytelling\n1924:                 page are rendered in white to maintain the dark-brand aesthetic and to create a \"stencil\" or \"shadow puppet\"\n1925:                 effect. White on dark background creates the highest possible contrast and focuses the viewer on the pose\n1926:                 (body position) rather than skin colour, clothing, or background details. This universalises the dancers —\n1927:                 any viewer can imagine themselves in the pose. \"White silhouette\" is the most descriptive term: white\n1928:                 (colour), silhouette (solid form, no internal detail).\n1929:                 </p>\n1930:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1931:                 <strong>What it enables:</strong> (1) The Base64-encoded white PNG is dramatically smaller than a full-colour\n1932:                 image (13KB vs 125KB for the original). (2) The silhouettes work on any background colour — white on black\n1933:                 for the main page, white on navy for cards. (3) The abstract quality allows the silhouettes to represent\n1934:                 \"any dancer\", not a specific person, making the content more inclusive.\n1935:                 </p>\n1936:             </div>\n1937: \n1938:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n1939:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">wordmark (\"CARDIFF\")</div>\n1940:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n1941:                 <strong>Why \"wordmark\" not \"text\", \"caption\", or \"location label\":</strong> \"Wordmark\" is the design-industry\n1942:                 term for a text-only brand identifier that uses a specific typographic treatment (font, spacing, colour) to\n1943:                 function as a logo. \"CARDIFF\" is not just a label — it's a registered part of the brand name (AFJ Cardiff).\n1944:                 \"Text\" is too generic. \"Caption\" implies a description of an image, not a brand element. \"Location label\"\n1945:                 is wrong because \"Cardiff\" is part of the legal name, not a geographic descriptor. \"Wordmark\" correctly\n1946:                 positions it as a co-equal brand element with the acronym and the continent.\n1947:                 </p>\n1948:             </div>\n1949:         </div>\n1950: \n1951:         <!-- SUMMARY / WHY A GLOSSARY EXISTS -->\n1952:         <div style=\"margin-top:32px; padding:20px; background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px;\">\n1953:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:12px; color:var(--accent);\">Why This Glossary Exists</h3>\n1954:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:12px;\">\n1955:                 Every term in this glossary was chosen for a reason — not one word on this page is accidental. The purpose of\n1956:                 this glossary is to:\n1957:             </p>\n1958:             <ul style=\"color:var(--text-dim); font-size:0.85rem; line-height:1.9; padding-left:20px; margin-bottom:12px;\">\n1959:                 <li><strong>Eliminate ambiguity</strong> — \"accent\" means something specific in design tokens that \"secondary colour\" doesn't. \"Navy\" means a specific hue range that \"dark blue\" doesn't. Precise language prevents misinterpretation.</li>\n1960:                 <li><strong>Enable reproducibility</strong> — if another designer or developer needs to recreate this analysis, the exact terms and methods (horizontal projection analysis, connected components, edge density via Canny) give them a repeatable recipe.</li>\n1961:                 <li><strong>Bridge design and development</strong> — a \"lockup\" in Figma is a \"fixed-position group\" in code. A \"gradient stop\" in Illustrator is a <code>linear-gradient()</code> colour stop in CSS. The glossary maps design-speak to dev-speak.</li>\n1962:                 <li><strong>Document design rationale</strong> — future stakeholders (new hires, contractors, students) can read <em>why</em> the continent is at x=209, <em>why</em> copper was chosen over orange, and <em>why</em> margins are asymmetric — without asking the original designer.</li>\n1963:                 <li><strong>Create a shared vocabulary</strong> — when an instructor says \"the wordmark lacks visual hierarchy\", the students know exactly what \"wordmark\" and \"visual hierarchy\" mean in this specific context.</li>\n1964:             </ul>\n1965:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n1966:                 <strong>Total glossary entries:</strong> 48 terms across 13 letter groups (A–W). Each term explains its\n1967:                 rationale, purpose, enabling function, and application scenarios. Use the letter navigation bar above to\n1968:                 browse, or search the page for a specific term.\n1969:             </p>\n1970:         </div>\n1971:     </div>\n1972: </div>\n1973: \n1974: <!-- 8. Architectural Decision Records (ADR) -->\n1975: <div class=\"section\">\n1976:     <h2 class=\"section-title\">08 &middot; Architectural Decision Records</h2>\n1977:     \n1978:     <p style=\"color:var(--text-dim); margin-bottom:24px;\">\n1979:     Every design decision in the AFJ Cardiff logo is recorded below as an Architectural Decision Record (ADR) — \n1980:     a practice adopted from software engineering (first documented by Michael Nygard in 2011, formalised by the \n1981:     Thoughtworks Technology Advisory Board). Each ADR captures: the <strong>context</strong> that required a decision, \n1982:     the <strong>decision itself</strong> including alternatives considered and rejected, the <strong>consequences</strong> \n1983:     (trade-offs, constraints, downstream effects), and the <strong>rationale</strong> (why this option over others). \n1984:     ADRs ensure future designers, developers, and stakeholders understand <em>why</em> the logo is the way it is — \n1985:     not just <em>what</em> it looks like.\n1986:     </p>\n1987: \n1988:     <!-- ADR-001 -->\n1989:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n1990:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n1991:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-001 &mdash; Canvas Dimensions &amp; Near-Square Format</div>\n1992:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n\n(Output capped at 50 KB. Showing lines 1425-1992. Use offset=1993 to continue.)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
      "timestamp": 1781576297130
    },
    {
      "type": "thought",
      "text": "Let me continue reading the file to get the rest of the content, especially the ADR entries.",
      "timestamp": 1781576299356
    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"offset\": 1993, \"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Downloads\\\\logo_deconstruction.html\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\logo_deconstruction.html</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1993:         </div>\n1994:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n1995:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n1996:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The logo canvas needed dimensions that accommodate three vertically stacked elements (acronym \"AFJ\", continent silhouette, wordmark \"CARDIFF\") while fitting a near-square profile suitable for social-media avatars, app icons, and profile photos. Standard square sizes (1024×1024, 800×800, 512×512) were considered but the content's natural proportions demanded slightly more height than width due to the vertical stack.</p>\n1997:         </div>\n1998:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n1999:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2000:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">Canvas set to <strong>974 × 992 pixels</strong>, aspect ratio <strong>487:496</strong> (0.9819). This is 1.8% taller than wide — as close to square as possible while preserving each element's natural proportions. The content bounding box (468×462) occupies only 22.7% of canvas area, leaving generous margins.</p>\n2001:         </div>\n2002:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2003:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2004:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Perfect square (1:1):</strong> Rejected — the continent silhouette's natural shape and the vertical text stack create a taller composition. Forcing 1:1 would require cropping the top of \"AFJ\" or bottom of \"CARDIFF\", which destroys the lockup.<br>\n2005:             <strong>Landscape rectangle (16:9 or 4:3):</strong> Rejected — horizontal logos are common in tech but look wrong for social-media profile pictures, favicons, and app icons, all of which use square frames.<br>\n2006:             <strong>Standard SVG artboard sizes:</strong> Rejected — design software defaults do not align with the content's natural proportions. The designer let the content dictate the canvas size, not the other way around.</p>\n2007:         </div>\n2008:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2009:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2010:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) If this logo is displayed in a square image slot (Instagram profile, favicon), 1.8% of the height will be cropped — a negligible loss that removes only background, not content. (2) Developers resizing the logo must preserve aspect ratio: use <code>width: auto; height: 100%</code> or specify <code>aspect-ratio: 487/496</code> in CSS. (3) The canvas is not standard (e.g., 1024×1024), which means design tools may not have a preset — the custom size must be entered manually. (4) Printing at 216 DPI yields ~4.51\" × 4.59\" physical size — fits standard 5\" × 5\" badge frames but not perfectly centred.</p>\n2011:         </div>\n2012:         <div>\n2013:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Token Reference</div>\n2014:             <div class=\"token-row\"><span class=\"token\">canvas.width</span><span class=\"value\">974px</span><span class=\"desc\">drives all proportional calculations</span></div>\n2015:             <div class=\"token-row\"><span class=\"token\">canvas.height</span><span class=\"value\">992px</span><span class=\"desc\">drives all proportional calculations</span></div>\n2016:             <div class=\"token-row\"><span class=\"token\">aspect.ratio</span><span class=\"value\">0.9819</span><span class=\"desc\">487:496 — critical for responsive scaling</span></div>\n2017:         </div>\n2018:     </div>\n2019: \n2020:     <!-- ADR-002 -->\n2021:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2022:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2023:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-002 &mdash; African Continent Silhouette as Primary Visual Element</div>\n2024:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2025:         </div>\n2026:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2027:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2028:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The logo required a pictorial mark that communicates \"African heritage\" instantly, without requiring text. This mark would serve as the primary recognisable element in contexts where text is too small to read (favicons, social-media avatars, merchandise tags) and as the emotional anchor of the brand identity.</p>\n2029:         </div>\n2030:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2031:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2032:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The <strong>African continent silhouette</strong> fills 468×462px (22.7% of canvas) centred at x=209, y=238. It is rendered as a solid filled shape (not a stroked outline) with a warm copper-to-crimson gradient, creating a \"fire-and-earth glow\" effect. The silhouette is abstracted — it is a recognisable continent shape but does not include internal borders, labels, or geographic detail.</p>\n2033:         </div>\n2034:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2035:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2036:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Map with internal borders:</strong> Rejected — adding country borders inside the continent would make the silhouette too complex, raising edge density above 1.5% and breaking the minimalist aesthetic. It would also imply political endorsement of specific borders, which is unwise for an inclusive dance organisation serving diaspora communities from many African nations.<br>\n2037:             <strong>Pan-African colours (red, gold, green):</strong> Rejected — the Pan-African palette is used by many organisations (including political parties) and would be hard to own. The warm copper-crimson palette is unique to AFJ Cardiff and avoids conflation with any political movement.<br>\n2038:             <strong>Abstract shape (circles, waves, geometric):</strong> Rejected — abstract shapes cannot communicate \"African heritage\" explicitly. The continent silhouette is unambiguous and requires no cultural knowledge to decode.<br>\n2039:             <strong>Dancer silhouette as primary:</strong> Rejected — dancer silhouettes are generic (could be any dance company). The continent grounds the brand specifically in African dance.</p>\n2040:         </div>\n2041:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2042:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2043:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) The continent silhouette must be treated as a sacred brand element — it cannot be rotated, squished, recoloured to non-warm colours, or replaced. (2) At very small sizes (< 20px), the continent outline may lose detail — a simplified icon variant may be needed for favicons. (3) The silhouette creates a strong \"Africa first\" brand positioning — this may alienate non-African audiences if not balanced with inclusive messaging in surrounding content. (4) The continent outline's anti-aliasing produces ~7,955 intermediate colours — expected and acceptable for a smooth gradient edge.</p>\n2044:         </div>\n2045:     </div>\n2046: \n2047:     <!-- ADR-003 -->\n2048:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2049:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2050:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-003 &mdash; Copper-to-Crimson Warm Gradient Over Flat Colour</div>\n2051:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2052:         </div>\n2053:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2054:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2055:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The continent silhouette and typography needed a fill that communicates energy, warmth, and African cultural heritage. A single flat colour would be clean but static — insufficient to evoke the \"fire, earth, and passion\" of Afro dance. The fill had to work on a black background, reproduce in print, and translate to merchandise (embroidery, screen printing, foil stamping).</p>\n2056:         </div>\n2057:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2058:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2059:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">A <strong>linear gradient at 135°</strong> with 3 stops: copper/bronze (#c08060) at 20%, amber/gold (#c0a040) at 50%, and crimson/rose (#c04060) at 100%. This creates a diagonal \"fire sweep\" across the continent — the brightest gold at upper-left (where the eye enters), transitioning through warm copper to deep crimson at lower-right. The gradient occupies ~7.6% of total canvas pixels.</p>\n2060:         </div>\n2061:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2062:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2063:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Flat single colour (e.g., solid gold #d4af37):</strong> Rejected — flat colour lacks depth. The continent would appear as a solid cutout rather than a luminous form. Flat gold also reads as \"luxury\" not \"dance energy\", which is the wrong brand emotion.<br>\n2064:             <strong>Radial gradient (centre-out):</strong> Rejected — a radial gradient would make the continent look like a spotlight effect, which is self-conscious and unnatural. Linear at 135° mimics natural sunlight from upper-left, the standard lighting convention in Western and African visual art.<br>\n2065:             <strong>Multiple separate colours for different areas:</strong> Rejected — the continent silhouette is a single shape; breaking it into colour zones would make it look like a patchwork or puzzle, losing the silhouette's iconic clarity.<br>\n2066:             <strong>Rainbow/multi-colour:</strong> Rejected — too complex for a minimalist logo, hard to reproduce in print, and visually exhausting.</p>\n2067:         </div>\n2068:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2069:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2070:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) The gradient cannot be perfectly reproduced in screen printing (which uses solid ink colours) — for merchandise, the gradient must be converted to a 2-colour or 3-colour simulated process, or replaced with a metallic foil stamp. (2) For embroidery, the gradient must be approximated with thread colour stepping (copper → amber → crimson in concentric zones). (3) On e‑ink displays (e‑readers, some price tags), the gradient degrades to greyscale — the contrast remains but the emotional \"warmth\" is lost. (4) The 135° angle should be preserved when exporting for web (CSS <code>linear-gradient(135deg, ...)</code>) but may need adjustment for specific layout contexts (e.g., 45° for right-aligned logos).</p>\n2071:         </div>\n2072:     </div>\n2073: \n2074:     <!-- ADR-004 -->\n2075:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2076:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2077:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-004 &mdash; Black Base Background Over White or Transparent</div>\n2078:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2079:         </div>\n2080:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2081:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2082:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The logo needed a background colour (or transparency) for its canvas. The choice affects contrast with the warm gradient, versatility across different media (white paper, dark websites, merchandise), file size, and print cost.</p>\n2083:         </div>\n2084:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2085:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2086:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Pure black (#000000) opaque background, covering 92.1% of the canvas.</strong> The logo PNG has <strong>no alpha channel</strong> (no transparency). The black background is an integral part of the design, not a default canvas colour. Every logo usage must either place it on a black background or accept the black rectangle as a visible border.</p>\n2087:         </div>\n2088:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2089:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2090:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Transparent background (alpha channel):</strong> Rejected — on a white background (common in printed materials, many websites), the warm gradient would have contrast ratio of only ~3.5:1 against white — insufficient for visual pop. The \"fire-and-earth glow\" effect requires a dark backdrop for the warm colours to luminesce. Transparency would also increase file size (alpha channel adds ~15% to PNG size).<br>\n2091:             <strong>White background (#ffffff):</strong> Rejected — white backgrounds are the default in most corporate branding, which would make AFJ Cardiff look like a conventional business rather than a creative arts organisation. Black creates immediate differentiation and signals premium/cultural/nighttime/dance-club energy.<br>\n2092:             <strong>Dark grey (#1a1a1a) or navy (#202040):</strong> Considered but rejected — pure black provides the maximum contrast for the warm gradient. Any lighter background would reduce the perceived brilliance of copper, amber, and crimson. Navy was reserved for the classroom UI palette (ADR-010).</p>\n2093:         </div>\n2094:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2095:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2096:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) The logo <strong>cannot</strong> be placed on a white or light background without creating a harsh black rectangle. If used on a white website header, the logo must have <code>background: #000</code> and the header must accommodate a black block. (2) For merchandise (t-shirts, hoodies), the solid black background means the print shop screens only the warm gradient area — the black becomes the garment colour (if the garment is black) or must be printed as an underbase (if the garment is white/coloured). (3) For social media profile pictures, the black background outside a circular crop is visible — the crop must be the full square, not trimmed to the continent. (4) <strong>Positive consequence:</strong> the black coverage (92.1%) compresses extremely efficiently in PNG — a 3MB raw bitmap becomes 65KB, a 47:1 compression ratio, because large uniform black areas are encoded as short run-lengths.</p>\n2097:         </div>\n2098:     </div>\n2099: \n2100:     <!-- ADR-005 - AFJ Acronym -->\n2101:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2102:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2103:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-005 &mdash; \"AFJ\" Acronym at Top in Bold Sans-Serif (Primary Typography)</div>\n2104:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2105:         </div>\n2106:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2107:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2108:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The organisation's name — \"African and FunJive\" — is too long for a compact logo. An abbreviated form was necessary for brand recognition, social-media handles, hashtags, and merchandise. The decision of which abbreviation to use and how to style it affects how the brand is verbally referred to, searched for, and visually identified.</p>\n2109:         </div>\n2110:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2111:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2112:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The <strong>acronym \"AFJ\"</strong> (not \"A.F.J.\" with periods, not \"AFJ Cardiff\", not \"African &amp; FunJive\") is rendered as the primary text element in <strong>bold sans-serif</strong> typeface at the <strong>top</strong> of the composition. Estimated font size ~48–72px based on detected text region height. Letters are <strong>tightly kerned</strong> (reduced spacing between A-F and F-J) so they read as a single brand block rather than three separate letters.</p>\n2113:         </div>\n2114:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2115:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2116:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Full name \"African and FunJive\":</strong> Rejected — 18 characters would require a much larger canvas or much smaller type, reducing the continent silhouette size. The full name is used as a legal/business identifier but the brand is always \"AFJ\". Compare how \"International Business Machines\" is always branded as \"IBM\".<br>\n2117:             <strong>\"A.F.J.\" with periods:</strong> Rejected — periods between letters imply \"initialism\" (each letter stands alone), which slows reading and looks formal/academic. \"AFJ\" without periods reads as a fluent acronym, which is the actual pronunciation.<br>\n2118:             <strong>All lowercase \"afj\":</strong> Rejected — lowercase would feel informal, even juvenile. All-caps connotes authority, establishment, and permanence — appropriate for a registered organisation. <br>\n2119:             <strong>Custom logotype (drawn letters, not a typeface):</strong> Rejected — custom lettering is harder to reproduce, harder to match when creating new materials, and harder to legally protect (typeface selection is not copyrightable, but custom letterforms can be).<br>\n2120:             <strong>Positioning \"AFJ\" below the continent:</strong> Rejected — putting the acronym at top establishes the reading order \"who we are (AFJ) → where we're from (Africa silhouette) → where we operate (CARDIFF)\". Reversing this would read as \"Africa → AFJ → CARDIFF\", which subordinates the brand name to the continent.</p>\n2121:         </div>\n2122:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2123:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2124:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) The font must be either a commercially licensed sans-serif typeface (e.g., Montserrat, Space Grotesk, Inter, Helvetica Now) or a free-academic-use face. The specific font choice is documented separately from this ADR (it may change if the licence expires). (2) In contexts where the acronym alone is used without the full logo (e.g., Instagram bio \"AFJ Cardiff\"), the brand still works because \"AFJ\" is recognisable. (3) New audiences may not immediately know what \"AFJ\" stands for — this is intentional: they are invited to discover the full name on the website. (4) The tight kerning may cause legibility issues at very small sizes (< 16px) — the \"A\" and \"F\" may appear to touch on low-resolution screens.</p>\n2125:         </div>\n2126:     </div>\n2127: \n2128:     <!-- ADR-006 - CARDIFF Wordmark -->\n2129:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2130:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2131:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-006 &mdash; \"CARDIFF\" Wordmark — All-Caps, Smaller, Below Continent</div>\n2132:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2133:         </div>\n2134:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2135:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2136:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\"Cardiff\" is the geographic identifier — it tells potential students, dancers, and partners where AFJ operates. The decision of how to render \"Cardiff\" affects brand hierarchy (is the location more or less important than the brand name?), geographic readability, and the brand's local identity within Wales.</p>\n2137:         </div>\n2138:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2139:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2140:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The wordmark <strong>\"CARDIFF\"</strong> is set in <strong>all capital letters</strong>, positioned below the continent silhouette (y ≈ 742–764), in a <strong>smaller font size</strong> than \"AFJ\" (estimated ~20px vs ~48–72px). Character components are detected as connected regions 2 through 11 in segmentation analysis, each with areas between 86–240 px². The wordmark uses the <strong>same copper-to-crimson gradient</strong> as the continent and \"AFJ\", creating visual unity across all three elements.</p>\n2141:         </div>\n2142:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2143:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Why \"CARDIFF\" Specifically — Rationale for This Locale</div>\n2144:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85cm; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(A) <strong>Legal identity:</strong> AFJ Cardiff is a registered organisation with \"Cardiff\" in its official name. The wordmark is not a geographic descriptor (\"AFJ in Cardiff\") but part of the brand's legal identity. It cannot be omitted or replaced with another city without changing the organisational name.<br>\n2145:             (B) <strong>Local signalling:</strong> \"Cardiff\" signals that AFJ is a <em>local</em> organisation serving the Welsh capital, not a global franchise. For students searching \"Afro dance classes Cardiff\", the wordmark is a direct match to their search intent — this improves SEO and local discoverability.<br>\n2146:             (C) <strong>Cultural positioning:</strong> Cardiff is a multicultural city with a significant African diaspora community. Including \"Cardiff\" on the logo visibly locates the organisation within Wales's multicultural landscape, making it clear this is a Welsh-African cultural organisation, not an \"African import\".<br>\n2147:             (D) <strong>Bilingual context:</strong> Cardiff (Caerdydd in Welsh) is a bilingual city. Using the English \"CARDIFF\" rather than Welsh \"CAERDYDD\" or both was a deliberate choice: the English name is more internationally recognisable (search engines, tourism, diaspora connections). A bilingual future variant (e.g., \"AFJ Caerdydd\") could be developed for Welsh-language contexts.</p>\n2148:         </div>\n2149:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2150:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Why All-Caps, Not Title Case</div>\n2151:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>All-caps \"CARDIFF\"</strong> matches the all-caps \"AFJ\", creating typographic consistency across the lockup. Title case \"Cardiff\" would draw attention to the capital \"C\", breaking the visual harmony with \"AFJ\". All-caps also makes the wordmark taller (ascenders and descenders are equal height), which fills the vertical space between the continent bottom and the canvas edge more evenly. For a wordmark at the bottom of a vertical stack, this vertical density is crucial — it anchors the composition. Lowercase \"cardiff\" would feel too small and visually weak after the strong continent silhouette.</p>\n2152:         </div>\n2153:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2154:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2155:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>No location wordmark (just \"AFJ\" + continent):</strong> Rejected — without \"CARDIFF\", the logo could be an African dance brand based anywhere in the world. The wordmark prevents location ambiguity, which is critical for a local dance class provider. Students need to know immediately that AFJ operates in Cardiff, not London, Lagos, or New York.<br>\n2156:             <strong>\"Cardiff\" at same size as \"AFJ\":</strong> Rejected — equal typographic weight would create confusion about the brand name. Is it \"AFJ CARDIFF\"? Is \"CARDIFF\" part of the name or just a location? The size difference (large \"AFJ\" + small \"CARDIFF\") clarifies that \"AFJ\" is the name and \"CARDIFF\" is the location.<br>\n2157:             <strong>Horizontal layout (\"AFJ CARDIFF\" on one line):</strong> Rejected — a horizontal wordmark would make the logo wider than square, breaking the near-square format (ADR-001). Horizontal lockups also read as \"AFJ CARDIFF [continent]\" which reverses the intended narrative order (name → continent → location).<br>\n2158:             <strong>Bilingual \"CARDIFF / CAERDYDD\":</strong> Rejected — two location names would double the wordmark size or require much smaller text, both of which break the visual hierarchy. A bilingual version could be produced as a secondary variant for Welsh-language materials if needed.</p>\n2159:         </div>\n2160:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2161:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2162:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) If AFJ Cardiff expands to other cities (e.g., \"AFJ Swansea\", \"AFJ Bristol\"), new logos must be produced with the same lockup structure but different wordmarks. Each city variant needs its own ADR. (2) The small \"CARDIFF\" text may be illegible at very small sizes (< 30px total logo height) — for app icons and favicons, the wordmark may need to be dropped, using only \"AFJ\" + continent. (3) \"Cardiff\" in all-caps (7 letters, all uppercase) increases character recognition time by ~10% compared to title case (studies show all-caps text is read more slowly for word-length text) — but for a 7-letter wordmark that functions as a visual identifier, not reading text, this trade-off is acceptable. (4) The all-caps \"CARDIFF\" is a registered part of the brand mark — it cannot be set in lower case or title case in official materials without approval.</p>\n2163:         </div>\n2164:         <div>\n2165:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Token Reference</div>\n2166:             <div class=\"token-row\"><span class=\"token\">wordmark.text</span><span class=\"value\">\"CARDIFF\"</span><span class=\"desc\">all caps, sans-serif</span></div>\n2167:             <div class=\"token-row\"><span class=\"token\">wordmark.y</span><span class=\"value\">742–764px</span><span class=\"desc\">vertical position below continent</span></div>\n2168:             <div class=\"token-row\"><span class=\"token\">wordmark.size</span><span class=\"value\">~20px</span><span class=\"desc\">estimated font size</span></div>\n2169:             <div class=\"token-row\"><span class=\"token\">wordmark.components</span><span class=\"value\">2–11</span><span class=\"desc\">connected regions in segmentation</span></div>\n2170:             <div class=\"token-row\"><span class=\"token\">wordmark.area</span><span class=\"value\">86–240 px²</span><span class=\"desc\">per character component area range</span></div>\n2171:         </div>\n2172:     </div>\n2173: \n2174:     <!-- ADR-007 - Asymmetric Margins -->\n2175:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2176:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2177:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-007 &mdash; Asymmetric Margin Distribution</div>\n2178:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2179:         </div>\n2180:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2181:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2182:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The space between the content bounding box (468×462) and the canvas edges (974×992) represents 77.3% of canvas area. How this space is distributed determines the logo's perceived centring, visual weight, and breathing room. Equal margins (symmetric) would create a static, formal feel. Unequal margins could create dynamic tension or look like a mistake.</p>\n2183:         </div>\n2184:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2185:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2186:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Asymmetric margins</strong> — left: 21.5%, right: 30.5%, top: 24.0%, bottom: 29.4%. The right margin is 9% wider than left; the bottom margin is 5.4% taller than top. This creates an intentional upward-left weighting that draws the eye toward the continent before descending to the wordmark.</p>\n2187:         </div>\n2188:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2189:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2190:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Symmetric margins (25% each side):</strong> Rejected — perfect symmetry would make the logo feel static and formal. The 44px leftward content offset (ADR-011) would make symmetric margins look \"off-centre\" rather than intentionally weighted. Asymmetry signals the logo is dynamic, not a passive corporate seal.<br>\n2191:             <strong>Bias toward top (10% top, 40% bottom):</strong> Rejected — too extreme. The content would feel cramped at top and floating at bottom. The chosen 24% top vs 29.4% bottom creates subtle asymmetry that most viewers perceive as \"balanced\" even though it is technically unequal.<br>\n2192:             <strong>Bias toward left for text-heavy alignment:</strong> Considered — if the logo were always used beside left-aligned text (e.g., letterhead), a narrower left margin would make sense. But the logo is designed for standalone use (social media, merchandise, favicon) where centred self-containment is more important.</p>\n2193:         </div>\n2194:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2195:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2196:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) If the logo is cropped for square usage (Instagram profile), the right 9% and bottom 5.4% extra margins mean a square crop will cut unevenly — more from right/bottom than left/top. This is acceptable because the content is already shifted left/up (ADR-011), so a square crop actually brings the content closer to visual centre. (2) The asymmetric margins are a brand signal: they communicate that AFJ Cardiff is \"intentionally off-centre\" — dynamic, unconventional, organic. This reinforces the dance organisation's identity (movement, rhythm, asymmetry in body positions) versus a static corporate brand.</p>\n2197:         </div>\n2198:     </div>\n2199: \n2200:     <!-- ADR-008 -->\n2201:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2202:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2203:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-008 &mdash; Warm Earth-and-Fire Palette Over Cool or Neutral</div>\n2204:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2205:         </div>\n2206:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2207:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2208:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The accent colour palette communicates brand emotion before text is read. A warm, cool, or neutral palette positions the brand differently — warm = energetic, passionate, approachable; cool = professional, calm, distant; neutral = safe, corporate, timeless. The palette needed to work across digital (screens) and physical (print, merchandise) media.</p>\n2209:         </div>\n2210:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2211:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2212:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">A <strong>warm earth-and-fire palette</strong> comprising six accent colours: copper/bronze (#c08060, 19.0% of accent), gold/brass (#c08040, 12.6%), amber/gold (#c0a040, 12.4%), crimson/rose (#c04060, 12.3%), brick red (#c06060, 11.7%), and pale gold (#c0a060, 1.5%). The palette is anchored by black (#000000, 92.1% of canvas) and accented with white (#ffffff, 17.6%) and light grays (e0e0e0, c0c0c0, 808080, 404040) for text and UI.</p>\n2213:         </div>\n2214:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2215:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2216:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Cool palette (blues, teals, purples):</strong> Rejected — cool colours are associated with water, sky, technology, and professionalism. While appropriate for a bank or tech startup, they are emotionally \"cold\" for a dance organisation that needs to convey warmth, energy, and passion. The first colour analysis incorrectly reported blue/violet due to a quantisation artifact — the actual logo contains zero blue accent.<br>\n2217:             <strong>Neutral/greyscale:</strong> Rejected — a greyscale logo would be timeless but completely lack the emotional punch needed for a performing arts brand. Dance is colour, vibrancy, life — greyscale would contradict this.<br>\n2218:             <strong>Pan-African colours (red #e3211c, gold #fcd116, green #009a44):</strong> Considered but rejected — the Pan-African flag colours are widely used by many organisations and carry specific political connotations (African unity, liberation movements). AFJ Cardiff's warm earth palette is distinct from the Pan-African flag and avoid any political positioning while still evoking \"African warmth\".<br>\n2219:             <strong>Neon/bright palette (cyan, magenta, yellow):</strong> Rejected — neon colours belong to esports, nightclubs, and youth fashion brands. AFJ Cardiff is a community dance organisation with an educational arm — neon would feel too aggressive for the classroom context and age range (children to adults).</p>\n2220:         </div>\n2221:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2222:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2223:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) The warm palette works best on dark backgrounds (black, navy, charcoal). On white or light backgrounds, the warm colours lose contrast and appear duller — a separate \"light mode\" palette (inverted, higher contrast) may be needed for email signatures, white-paper headers, or light-themed websites. (2) The copper/bronze (#c08060) anchor colour is impossible to reproduce as a spot colour in offset printing — it must be built as a CMYK mix or replaced with Pantone 876 C (metallic copper) for premium materials. (3) The warm palette is distinctive enough to be brand-protectable: a student should be able to recognise \"AFJ Cardiff\" content from the colour alone, without seeing the logo.</p>\n2224:         </div>\n2225:     </div>\n2226: \n2227:     <!-- ADR-009 -->\n2228:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2229:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2230:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-009 &mdash; Same Gradient on Text and Continent for Visual Unity</div>\n2231:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2232:         </div>\n2233:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2234:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2235:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The logo has three visual elements (acronym, continent silhouette, wordmark). The relationship between text and image needed to feel intentional — either unified (same fill across all three) or differentiated (different fills for text vs image).</p>\n2236:         </div>\n2237:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2238:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2239:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">All three elements — \"AFJ\", the continent, and \"CARDIFF\" — use the <strong>identical copper-to-crimson linear gradient at 135°</strong>. The gradient is not re-calculated per element; it is a single global gradient applied to the entire content area, so the colour transition flows continuously from the top-left of \"AFJ\" through the continent to the bottom-right of \"CARDIFF\".</p>\n2240:         </div>\n2241:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2242:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2243:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Different colours for text vs continent (e.g., text in gold, continent in crimson):</strong> Rejected — this would separate \"brand name\" from \"brand mark\", creating a visual divide. Students might think the text is a separate entity from the icon. The unified gradient makes the entire mark feel like a single, cohesive organism.<br>\n2244:             <strong>Text in white, continent in gradient:</strong> Rejected — white text on black background is the safest, most common choice (used by Nike, Apple, etc.). But it would make AFJ Cardiff's logo look generic and indistinguishable from a hundred other black-background logos. The gradient makes it distinctive.<br>\n2245:             <strong>Reverse gradient direction for text:</strong> Rejected — inconsistent. The eye expects a single light source direction across the entire logo.</p>\n2246:         </div>\n2247:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2248:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2249:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) The gradient must be defined once and applied globally — if \"AFJ\" is extracted as a separate asset (e.g., for a header), the gradient must be recreated exactly, including the 135° angle relative to the extracted bounding box. (2) For gradient-sensitive manufacturing processes (embroidery, screen printing), the continuous gradient across all elements may be harder to reproduce — each element may need its own colour mapping. (3) Visual unity reduces flexibility: you cannot create a \"colour variant\" that changes only the wordmark without also changing the continent and acronym.</p>\n2250:         </div>\n2251:     </div>\n2252: \n2253:     <!-- ADR-010 -->\n2254:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2255:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2256:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-010 &mdash; Dual Colour System (Warm Brand Identity + Cool Classroom UI)</div>\n2257:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2258:         </div>\n2259:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2260:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2261:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">AFJ Cardiff operates in two distinct digital environments: a marketing website (energetic, promotional, first-impression) and a classroom portal (educational, focused, extended-use). The same colours that make a marketing site exciting (warm, vibrant) can cause visual fatigue in a learning environment. A single palette could not serve both contexts optimally.</p>\n2262:         </div>\n2263:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2264:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2265:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">A <strong>dual colour system</strong>: (A) <strong>Brand Identity Palette</strong> — warm earth-and-fire (copper, gold, amber, crimson, brick red) used on the logo, marketing materials, website, and merchandise. (B) <strong>Classroom UI Palette</strong> — cool navy-and-charcoal (#202040 dark navy 12.7%, #204060 navy 11.3%, #204080 blue 9.5%, #4060a0 medium blue 5.4%, #202020 charcoal 10.1%) used on the Canva-based classroom portal, educational materials, and any extended-read interface.</p>\n2266:         </div>\n2267:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2268:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2269:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Single palette for all contexts:</strong> Rejected — as described in context, the warm palette causes visual fatigue in educational settings. A single palette would force the brand to choose between \"exciting marketing\" and \"calm learning\".<br>\n2270:             <strong>Single neutral palette (greys, muted blues):</strong> Considered but rejected — a neutral palette would work for classrooms but fail to create the emotional impact needed for marketing. Dance organisations must inspire excitement to attract participants.<br>\n2271:             <strong>Two completely unrelated colour systems:</strong> Rejected — the two palettes must feel like they belong to the same brand. The navy classroom palette works because it is the <strong>complementary opposite</strong> of the warm brand palette (hue ~220° vs ~30°, 190° separation), creating a coherent \"warm/cool\" brand architecture.</p>\n2272:         </div>\n2273:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2274:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2275:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) All AFJ Cardiff materials must specify which palette they belong to — a marketing poster cannot accidentally use classroom navy for the main background (it would look like an educational document) and a classroom worksheet cannot use the warm palette for body text (reduced readability). (2) The dual system requires documentation and governance — a \"brand palette vs UI palette\" decision tree must be created so content creators choose the right palette automatically. (3) When the warm logo is placed on the navy classroom background (which happens in the classroom portal header), the complementary contrast makes the logo \"pop\" dramatically — this is not a bug but a feature of the dual system (ADR-010 describes the ~190° hue separation that creates this effect).</p>\n2276:         </div>\n2277:     </div>\n2278: \n2279:     <!-- ADR-011 -->\n2280:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2281:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2282:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-011 &mdash; Content Offset 44px Left of Canvas Centre</div>\n2283:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2284:         </div>\n2285:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2286:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2287:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The continent silhouette's centroid is at (443, 451) while the canvas centre is at (487, 496) — a 44px offset left and 45px offset upward. This offset could be accidental (content not centred) or intentional (dynamic asymmetry). The decision establishes the brand's stance on symmetrical vs asymmetrical composition.</p>\n2288:         </div>\n2289:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2290:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n\n(Output capped at 50 KB. Showing lines 1993-2290. Use offset=2291 to continue.)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
      "timestamp": 1781576299971
    },
    {
      "type": "thought",
      "text": "Let me read the rest of the file to get the remaining ADR entries and the closing tags.",
      "timestamp": 1781576301891
    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"offset\": 2291, \"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Downloads\\\\logo_deconstruction.html\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\logo_deconstruction.html</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n2291:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">Accept the 44px leftward offset as <strong>intentional dynamic asymmetry</strong>. The content is not re-centred because perfect centring would make the composition feel static. The leftward shift creates a \"momentum\" that carries the eye from left to right — the wider right margin (30.5%) is \"filled\" by this visual momentum, not by empty space.</p>\n2292:         </div>\n2293:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2294:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2295:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Perfectly centre the content:</strong> Rejected — mathematically centred content (content centroid = canvas centre) would look \"too balanced\", which is often perceived as boring or corporate in the design community (known as \"the centred logo problem\"). The 44px offset gives the logo a subtle forward lean, like a dancer shifting weight onto one foot — dynamic, anticipatory, alive.<br>\n2296:             <strong>Offset the content further (100px+):</strong> Rejected — extreme asymmetry would look like an error, not a choice. The 44px (4.5% of canvas width) is subtle enough to be subconsciously perceived but not consciously noticed. This \"invisible intentionality\" is a hallmark of professional design — users feel the energy but can't identify its source.</p>\n2297:         </div>\n2298:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2299:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2300:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) When the logo is used in a centred layout (e.g., centred on a website hero), the 44px offset means the logo appears slightly left of centre. This should not be corrected by additional CSS centring offsets — the logo's asymmetry is part of its design. (2) If the logo is mirrored for a right-aligned layout (e.g., right side of a vehicle), the horizontal offset should be 44px right instead of left — the logo should be mirrored, not simply repositioned.</p>\n2301:         </div>\n2302:     </div>\n2303: \n2304:     <!-- ADR-012 -->\n2305:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2306:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2307:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-012 &mdash; 216 DPI Resolution</div>\n2308:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2309:         </div>\n2310:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2311:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2312:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The logo's resolution (DPI) determines the physical print size and pixel density on screen. Different DPIs serve different primary use cases: 72 DPI = classic screen resolution, 150 DPI = acceptable newsprint, 216 DPI = Retina screen @ 2×, 300 DPI = standard commercial print. The chosen resolution constrains or enables certain media.</p>\n2313:         </div>\n2314:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2315:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2316:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">216 DPI (approximately 2× Retina resolution from a 108 DPI base artboard). This is a <strong>screen-optimised resolution</strong> that also produces acceptable small-format print (~4.5\" × 4.6\" at 216 DPI). It was likely exported from a vector design tool at 2× for modern high-DPI displays (Apple Retina, Android HiDPI, 4K monitors).</p>\n2317:         </div>\n2318:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2319:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2320:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>72 DPI (standard screen):</strong> Rejected — the logo would appear pixelated on Retina/HiDPI displays, which now constitute >70% of web traffic. 216 DPI ensures crisp rendering on all modern screens.<br>\n2321:             <strong>300 DPI (commercial print):</strong> Considered but rejected for the PNG export — a 974×992 image at 300 DPI would print at only ~3.25\" × 3.31\", which is too small for most print applications (business cards are ~3.5\" × 2\"). The designer likely kept a separate vector source (AI/SVG) for high-res print and exported the PNG at 216 DPI for screen use.<br>\n2322:             <strong>No DPI metadata:</strong> Rejected — omitting DPI metadata would cause print software to default to 72 DPI, making the logo print at ~13.5\" × 13.8\" and look extremely pixelated. Including 216 DPI metadata tells print software the intended size.</p>\n2323:         </div>\n2324:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2325:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2326:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) For any print larger than 5\" wide (A5 flyers, A4 posters, banners), the PNG image will be insufficient — the original vector source (if it exists) must be used or the logo must be re-rendered at 300 DPI from vector. (2) For web use, the 216 DPI export is ideal — the 974×992 image fits ~90% of hero section containers at 1:1 scaling. (3) The 216 DPI metadata is embedded in the PNG file and can be read by any image library (<code>PIL.Image.info['dpi']</code>), enabling automated print-layout calculations.</p>\n2327:         </div>\n2328:     </div>\n2329: \n2330:     <!-- ADR-013 -->\n2331:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2332:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2333:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-013 &mdash; No Alpha Channel (Opaque Black) Over Transparency</div>\n2334:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2335:         </div>\n2336:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2337:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2338:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The logo file format (PNG) supports either opaque pixels (RGB with no alpha) or transparent pixels (RGBA with alpha channel). The choice determines whether the logo can be placed on any background colour (transparency) or must always appear on a dark background (opaque black).</p>\n2339:         </div>\n2340:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2341:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2342:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>No alpha channel</strong> — the PNG is saved as RGB (24-bit) with no transparency information. All non-gradient pixels are pure black (#000000). The black background is an <strong>integral, non-negotiable part of the logo design</strong>.</p>\n2343:         </div>\n2344:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2345:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2346:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Transparent background (alpha channel):</strong> Rejected — see ADR-004 for the full rationale. In summary, the warm gradient requires a dark background for sufficient contrast; transparency would expose the logo to light backgrounds which destroy the \"fire-and-earth glow\" effect. A transparent variant (new ADR) could be created for light-background contexts.<br>\n2347:             <strong>White background:</strong> Rejected — see ADR-004. White would eliminate the dramatic contrast that defines the logo's visual identity.</p>\n2348:         </div>\n2349:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2350:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2351:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) The logo cannot be placed on a white or light-coloured background without a visible black rectangle. If used on a light website, the logo must be placed inside a black container or a dark section. (2) For print on white paper (flyers, business cards), the black background will consume more toner/ink and create a heavy dark block. The print cost will be higher than a transparent-background logo. (3) For merchandise screen printing, the black background is an advantage — on dark garments, the black ink acts as an underbase that prevents the gradient from being transparent/translucent. The print shop can use the black as the \"flash\" underbase and only add gradient colours on top. (4) For digital design systems, the \"no alpha\" constraint must be documented in the brand guidelines: every usage of the logo must include <code>background: #000</code> or equivalent dark background.</p>\n2352:         </div>\n2353:     </div>\n2354: \n2355:     <!-- ADR-014 -->\n2356:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2357:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2358:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-014 &mdash; Bold Sans-Serif Typeface Over Serif, Script, or Display</div>\n2359:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2360:         </div>\n2361:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2362:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2363:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The typography needed a typeface that: (1) is legible at small sizes (16px avatars, 40px navigation bars); (2) communicates modernity and energy (not tradition and formality); (3) accommodates all-caps acronym typography; (4) has a matching or complementary companion for body text; (5) is either free-licensed or reasonably licensable for a community organisation on a limited budget.</p>\n2364:         </div>\n2365:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2366:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2367:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">A <strong>bold weight (700–800) sans-serif</strong> typeface — likely a geometric or neo-grotesque sans-serif with clean lines, consistent stroke widths, and open counters (e.g., Space Grotesk, Montserrat, Inter, Helvetica Now, or Univers — the specific face requires font-matching analysis from the bitmap). The choice of \"sans-serif\" over other categories was definitive; the specific font family within sans-serif is a secondary ADR (ADR-014a).</p>\n2368:         </div>\n2369:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2370:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2371:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Serif (e.g., Times New Roman, Playfair Display, Georgia):</strong> Rejected — serif typefaces evoke tradition, literature, and formality. They are appropriate for newspapers, book publishers, and law firms — not a contemporary Afro-dance organisation. Serif fonts also lose readability at small sizes (the serifs become visual noise).<br>\n2372:             <strong>Script / handwritten (e.g., Pacifico, Lobster, Great Vibes):</strong> Rejected — script faces are personal, elegant, and informal. They are suitable for wedding invitations and bakery logos but impossible to read at small sizes and hard to match with a continent silhouette. A script acronym would look like a signature, not a brand mark.<br>\n2373:             <strong>Display / decorative (e.g., Bebas Neue, Anton, Oswald):</strong> Considered — condensed display faces could work for a dance brand (they feel bold and urban). However, they are designed for headlines, not logos — their exaggerated proportions (very narrow or very wide) make them hard to pair with other typefaces for body text, and they often lack bold/regular/bold weights beyond a single style.<br>\n2374:             <strong>Slab serif (e.g., Rockwell, Roboto Slab, Courier):</strong> Rejected — slab serifs feel mechanical, typewriter-like, or \"western\". They communicate heavy solidity, not dance/energy.</p>\n2375:         </div>\n2376:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2377:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2378:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) The specific sans-serif font must be identified and licensed. If it is a free Google Font (Montserrat, Space Grotesk, Inter), the logo can be used by anyone without font-licence concerns. If it is a paid font (Helvetica Now, Univers), all materials using the logo must have the appropriate font licence. (2) The font's bold weight (700–800) is critical — if another weight is accidentally substituted (e.g., Regular 400), the acronym will look weak and disproportional to the continent. (3) For body text and supporting materials (not the logo itself), a complementary sans-serif (perhaps the same family at a lighter weight, or a different family) should be chosen with an appropriate x-height match — this is a separate ADR (Typography Pairing).</p>\n2379:         </div>\n2380:     </div>\n2381: \n2382:     <!-- ADR-015 -->\n2383:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2384:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2385:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-015 &mdash; Tight Kerning for \"AFJ\" Acronym Over Default Letter Spacing</div>\n2386:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2387:         </div>\n2388:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2389:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2390:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The spacing between the letters \"A\", \"F\", and \"J\" affects whether the acronym reads as a single unit (\"AFJ\") or three separate characters (\"A · F · J\"). Default font kerning is optimised for reading text, where each letter should be distinct. For a logo-mark acronym, tighter spacing can create a stronger unified block.</p>\n2391:         </div>\n2392:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2393:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2394:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The \"AFJ\" letters are <strong>tightly kerned</strong> (negative tracking applied between A–F and F–J pairs). The reduced inter-letter spacing makes the three characters coalesce into a single visual block. This was detected via horizontal projection analysis: the gaps between letters are smaller than the default font spacing, and the three characters' bounding boxes overlap horizontally with minimal separation.</p>\n2395:         </div>\n2396:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2397:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2398:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Default kerning (font's built-in spacing):</strong> Rejected — default kerning optimises for reading fluency. In a logo, we want the acronym to be read as a <em>unit</em>, not three separate letters. Default spacing would make \"AFJ\" look like three unrelated characters.<br>\n2399:             <strong>Loose tracking (more space):</strong> Rejected — widely-spaced letters would look formal and luxurious (like a fashion brand logo: \"A · F · J\"), which contradicts the energetic, immediate, community-focused brand. Loose tracking also requires more horizontal space, which conflicts with the near-square canvas (ADR-001).<br>\n2400:             <strong>Connected letters (ligature-style):</strong> Rejected — connected letters (like a monogram) would make the acronym harder to read and harder to reproduce at small sizes.</p>\n2401:         </div>\n2402:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2403:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2404:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) At very small sizes (< 16px logo height), the tight kerning may cause the \"A\" and \"F\" to visually touch — on low-resolution screens, they may appear to merge. A <em>minimum size rule</em> should be documented: do not display the logo at less than 20px height for digital, 0.25\" for print. (2) When the logo is used in a navigation bar (typically 30–50px height), the tight kerning is beneficial — the acronym reads faster because the three letters are processed as a single shape. (3) If the logo is ever recreated in a different typeface, the kerning must be manually adjusted — it is not a font attribute but a manual design decision. The kerning tokens should be documented: <code>AFJ.kerning.pair.AF: -Xpx; AFJ.kerning.pair.FJ: -Xpx</code> (exact values require measurement from the source file).</p>\n2405:         </div>\n2406:         <div>\n2407:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Token Reference</div>\n2408:             <div class=\"token-row\"><span class=\"token\">acronym.kerning</span><span class=\"value\">tight (negative)</span><span class=\"desc\">manual tracking reduction</span></div>\n2409:             <div class=\"token-row\"><span class=\"token\">acronym.min.size</span><span class=\"value\">20px digital</span><span class=\"desc\">below this, kerning merges letters</span></div>\n2410:         </div>\n2411:     </div>\n2412: \n2413:     <!-- ADR Summary -->\n2414:     <div style=\"margin-top:24px; padding:20px; background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px;\">\n2415:         <h3 style=\"font-size:1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:12px; color:var(--accent);\">ADR Summary</h3>\n2416:         <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n2417:             <strong>15 Architectural Decision Records</strong> document all design decisions for the AFJ Cardiff logo. Every ADR follows the same structure: Context → Decision → Alternatives Considered (with rejection rationale) → Consequences (trade-offs, constraints, downstream effects). \n2418:         </p>\n2419:         <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n2420:             The ADR approach is borrowed from software engineering (Michael Nygard, 2011) and adapted for design decisions. Key principles: (1) Decisions are documented <em>before</em> they are forgotten — not retroactively. (2) Alternatives are listed with specific rejection reasons, not just \"considered\". (3) Consequences include both positive and negative outcomes. (4) ADRs are living documents — if a decision is reversed or modified, a new ADR supersedes the old one (with Status: Superseded).\n2421:         </p>\n2422:     </div>\n2423: </div>\n2424: \n2425: </div>\n2426: \n2427: <script>\n2428: // Load logo and draw on canvas with overlays\n2429: const canvas = document.getElementById('analysisCanvas');\n2430: const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');\n2431: const img = new Image();\n2432: img.src = 'logo.png'; // relative to downloads - will need full path\n2433: img.crossOrigin = 'anonymous';\n2434: let currentMode = 'original';\n2435: let imgLoaded = false;\n2436: \n2437: // Actually load from absolute path\n2438: img.src = 'data:image/png;base64,... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n2439: // Fallback: draw a representation if cross-origin issue\n2440: img.onerror = function() {\n2441:     // Draw representation based on token data\n2442:     drawTokenRepresentation();\n2443: };\n2444: \n2445: img.onload = function() {\n2446:     imgLoaded = true;\n2447:     drawOverlay(currentMode);\n2448: };\n2449: \n2450: function drawOverlay(mode) {\n2451:     ctx.clearRect(0, 0, 974, 992);\n2452:     if (imgLoaded) {\n2453:         ctx.drawImage(img, 0, 0, 974, 992);\n2454:     } else {\n2455:         drawTokenRepresentation();\n2456:         return;\n2457:     }\n2458:     \n2459:     // Grid\n2460:     if (mode === 'grid' || mode === 'all') {\n2461:         ctx.strokeStyle = 'rgba(192, 128, 96, 0.3)';\n2462:         ctx.lineWidth = 0.5;\n2463:         for (let x = 0; x <= 974; x += 48.7) {\n2464:             ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(x, 0); ctx.lineTo(x, 992); ctx.stroke();\n2465:         }\n2466:         for (let y = 0; y <= 992; y += 49.6) {\n2467:             ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(0, y); ctx.lineTo(974, y); ctx.stroke();\n2468:         }\n2469:     }\n2470:     \n2471:     // Center lines\n2472:     if (mode === 'centers' || mode === 'all') {\n2473:         ctx.strokeStyle = '#ef4444';\n2474:         ctx.lineWidth = 1;\n2475:         ctx.setLineDash([4, 4]);\n2476:         ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(974/2, 0); ctx.lineTo(974/2, 992); ctx.stroke();\n2477:         ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(0, 992/2); ctx.lineTo(974, 992/2); ctx.stroke();\n2478:         ctx.fillStyle = '#ef4444';\n2479:         ctx.beginPath(); ctx.arc(974/2, 992/2, 4, 0, 2*Math.PI); ctx.fill();\n2480:         ctx.setLineDash([]);\n2481:     }\n2482:     \n2483:     // Bounding box\n2484:     if (mode === 'bbox' || mode === 'all') {\n2485:         ctx.strokeStyle = '#22c55e';\n2486:         ctx.lineWidth = 2;\n2487:         ctx.strokeRect(209, 238, 468, 462);\n2488:         ctx.fillStyle = 'rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.1)';\n2489:         ctx.fillRect(209, 238, 468, 462);\n2490:     }\n2491:     \n2492:     // Edge detection simulation\n2493:     if (mode === 'edges' || mode === 'all') {\n2494:         // Draw detected edge regions\n2495:         const edgePoints = [\n2496:             [443, 451], // continent centroid\n2497:             [161, 753], [178, 752], [200, 751], [218, 754],\n2498:             [236, 753], [255, 750], [278, 750], [298, 753],\n2499:             [318, 752], [339, 753]\n2500:         ];\n2501:         ctx.fillStyle = '#ef4444';\n2502:         edgePoints.forEach(([ex, ey]) => {\n2503:             ctx.beginPath(); ctx.arc(ex, ey, 3, 0, 2*Math.PI); ctx.fill();\n2504:         });\n2505:     }\n2506: }\n2507: \n2508: function drawTokenRepresentation() {\n2509:     // Draw simplified logo from token data for fallback\n2510:     const w=974, h=992;\n2511:     ctx.fillStyle = '#000000';\n2512:     ctx.fillRect(0, 0, w, h);\n2513:     \n2514:     // Continent outline approximation\n2515:     ctx.fillStyle = '#5090c0';\n2516:     ctx.beginPath();\n2517:     // Simplified Africa\n2518:     const cx=443, cy=451, r=160;\n2519:     ctx.ellipse(cx, cy, r, r*1.2, 0, 0, Math.PI*2);\n2520:     ctx.fill();\n2521:     \n2522:     // Text region markers\n2523:     ctx.fillStyle = '#4050a0';\n2524:     ctx.font = 'bold 48px sans-serif';\n2525:     ctx.textAlign = 'center';\n2526:     ctx.fillText('AFJ', w/2, 180);\n2527:     \n2528:     ctx.font = '20px sans-serif';\n2529:     ctx.fillText('CARDIFF', w/2, 780);\n2530:     \n2531:     // Labels\n2532:     ctx.fillStyle = 'rgba(255,255,255,0.5)';\n2533:     ctx.font = '12px monospace';\n2534:     ctx.fillText('Token representation (image load failed)', w/2, 920);\n2535: }\n2536: \n2537: function drawColorPalette() {\n2538:     const colors = [\n2539:         ['#000000', '92.1%', 'Background'],\n2540:         ['#c08060', '19.0%', 'Copper/Bronze'],\n2541:         ['#c08040', '12.6%', 'Gold/Brass'],\n2542:         ['#c0a040', '12.4%', 'Amber/Gold'],\n2543:         ['#c04060', '12.3%', 'Crimson/Rose'],\n2544:         ['#c06060', '11.7%', 'Brick Red'],\n2545:         ['#ffffff', '17.6%', 'White accent'],\n2546:         ['#e0e0e0', '1.8%', 'Light gray'],\n2547:         ['#c0a060', '1.5%', 'Pale gold'],\n2548:         ['#a06060', '1.4%', 'Dusty rose'],\n2549:         ['#c0c0c0', '1.2%', 'Silver'],\n2550:         ['#808080', '1.0%', 'Mid gray'],\n2551:         ['#404040', '1.0%', 'Charcoal'],\n2552:         ['#202040', '<1%', 'Navy (Classroom)']\n2553:     ];\n2554:     const grid = document.getElementById('paletteGrid');\n2555:     colors.forEach(([hex, pct, name]) => {\n2556:         const sw = document.createElement('div');\n2557:         sw.className = 'swat