careful PowerShell script.\n\nFor glossary entries, the full transformation is:\n\nEntry start: Replace `<div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">` with `<details class=\"collapse glossary-item\">`\n\nTerm name: Replace `<div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">` with `<summary>`\nand `</div>` (at end of term name) with `</summary>\\n                <div class=\"collapse-body\">`\n\nWait, this is getting complicated with 48 different term names. \n\nLet me try yet another approach. What if I use PowerShell to do a more sophisticated transformation using a regex that captures the opening, term name, content, and closing?\n\nHere's a regex pattern for each glossary entry:\n\n```\n(?s)            <div style=\"background:var\\(--surface2\\); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var\\(--accent\\);\">\\n                <div style=\"font-family:var\\(--mono\\); font-size:0\\.9rem; color:var\\(--accent\\); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">(.*?)</div>\\n(.*?)            </div>\n```\n\nThis captures the term name in group 1 and the content in group 2.\n\nReplacement: \n```\n            <details class=\"collapse glossary-item\">\\n                <summary>$1</summary>\\n                <div class=\"collapse-body\">\\n$2                </div>\\n            </details>\n```\n\nWait, I need to be careful with the content indentation. After the term name div is removed, the content paragraphs are indented further. Let me look at the actual indentation.\n\nFrom the file:\n```\n            <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n                <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">accent gradient</div>\n     